examples.annotated_text: Yuan_dynasty: Despite the high position given to Muslims, some policies of the [dblookup('Yuan Emperors', 'Policies Against Muslims') -> Restriction of Halal Slaughter, Circumcision, Kosher Butchering] Yuan Emperors severely discriminated against them, restricting Halal slaughter and other Islamic practices like circumcision, as well as Kosher butchering for Jews, forcing them to eat food the Mongol way. Toward the end, [dblookup('Yuan Dynasty', 'Dissatisfaction Among Muslims') -> Corruption and Persecution] corruption and the persecution became so severe that Muslim generals joined Han Chinese in rebelling against the Mongols. The [dblookup('Zhu Yuanzhang', 'Role') -> Ming Founder] Ming founder Zhu Yuanzhang had Muslim generals like Lan Yu who rebelled against the Mongols and defeated them in combat. Some Muslim communities had a Chinese surname which meant "barracks" and could also mean "thanks". Many [dblookup('Hui Muslims', 'Contribution to Mongol Overthrow') -> Assisted Han Chinese] Hui Muslims claim this is because that they played an important role in overthrowing the Mongols and it was given in thanks by the Han Chinese for assisting them. During the war fighting the Mongols, among the Ming Emperor [dblookup('Zhu Yuanzhang', 'Muslim Generals') -> Feng Sheng] Zhu Yuanzhang's armies was the Hui Muslim Feng Sheng. The Muslims in the semu class also revolted against the Yuan dynasty in the Ispah Rebellion but the rebellion was crushed and the Muslims were massacred by the [dblookup('Ispah Rebellion', 'Suppressed By') -> Chen Youding] Yuan loyalist commander Chen Youding.
examples.text: Yuan_dynasty: Despite the high position given to Muslims, some policies of the Yuan Emperors severely discriminated against them, restricting Halal slaughter and other Islamic practices like circumcision, as well as Kosher butchering for Jews, forcing them to eat food the Mongol way. Toward the end, corruption and the persecution became so severe that Muslim generals joined Han Chinese in rebelling against the Mongols. The Ming founder Zhu Yuanzhang had Muslim generals like Lan Yu who rebelled against the Mongols and defeated them in combat. Some Muslim communities had a Chinese surname which meant "barracks" and could also mean "thanks". Many Hui Muslims claim this is because that they played an important role in overthrowing the Mongols and it was given in thanks by the Han Chinese for assisting them. During the war fighting the Mongols, among the Ming Emperor Zhu Yuanzhang's armies was the Hui Muslim Feng Sheng. The Muslims in the semu class also revolted against the Yuan dynasty in the Ispah Rebellion but the rebellion was crushed and the Muslims were massacred by the Yuan loyalist commander Chen Youding.

examples.annotated_text: European_Union_law: European Union law is a body of treaties and legislation, such as Regulations and Directives, which have direct effect or indirect effect on the laws of [dblookup('European Union law', 'Jurisdiction') -> European Union member states] European Union member states. The three sources of European Union law are [dblookup('European Union law', 'Sources') -> primary law, secondary law, supplementary law] primary law, secondary law and supplementary law. The main sources of [dblookup('Primary law', 'Examples') -> Treaties establishing the European Union] primary law are the Treaties establishing the European Union. [dblookup('Secondary law', 'Components') -> regulations, directives] Secondary sources include regulations and directives which are based on the Treaties. The legislature of the European Union is principally composed of the [dblookup('European Union legislature', 'Components') -> European Parliament, Council of the European Union] European Parliament and the Council of the European Union, which under the Treaties may establish secondary law to pursue the objective set out in the Treaties.
examples.text: European_Union_law: European Union law is a body of treaties and legislation, such as Regulations and Directives, which have direct effect or indirect effect on the laws of European Union member states. The three sources of European Union law are primary law, secondary law and supplementary law. The main sources of primary law are the Treaties establishing the European Union. Secondary sources include regulations and directives which are based on the Treaties. The legislature of the European Union is principally composed of the European Parliament and the Council of the European Union, which under the Treaties may establish secondary law to pursue the objective set out in the Treaties.

examples.annotated_text: Scottish_Parliament: The outcome of most votes can be predicted beforehand since [dblookup('Scottish_Parliament', 'Voting Instructions') -> political parties normally instruct members which way to vote] political parties normally instruct members which way to vote. Parties entrust some MSPs, known as [dblookup('Scottish_Parliament', 'Enforcers of Party Voting') -> whips] whips, with the task of ensuring that party members vote according to the party line. MSPs do not tend to vote against such instructions, since those who do are [dblookup('Members of the Scottish Parliament', 'Consequences of Voting Against Party Line') -> unlikely to reach higher political ranks] unlikely to reach higher political ranks in their parties. Errant members can be [dblookup('Members of the Scottish Parliament', 'Potential Consequence for Disobedience') -> deselected as official party candidates] deselected as official party candidates during future elections, and, in serious cases, may be [dblookup('Members of the Scottish Parliament', 'Severe Consequence for Disobedience') -> expelled from their parties] expelled from their parties outright. Thus, as with many Parliaments, the [dblookup('Scottish_Parliament', 'Member Independence Level') -> low] independence of Members of the Scottish Parliament tends to be low, and backbench rebellions by members who are discontent with their party's policies are rare. In some circumstances, however, parties announce [dblookup('Scottish_Parliament', 'Free Vote Circumstances') -> on moral issues] "free votes", which allows Members to vote as they please. This is typically done on moral issues.
examples.text: Scottish_Parliament: The outcome of most votes can be predicted beforehand since political parties normally instruct members which way to vote. Parties entrust some MSPs, known as whips, with the task of ensuring that party members vote according to the party line. MSPs do not tend to vote against such instructions, since those who do are unlikely to reach higher political ranks in their parties. Errant members can be deselected as official party candidates during future elections, and, in serious cases, may be expelled from their parties outright. Thus, as with many Parliaments, the independence of Members of the Scottish Parliament tends to be low, and backbench rebellions by members who are discontent with their party's policies are rare. In some circumstances, however, parties announce "free votes", which allows Members to vote as they please. This is typically done on moral issues.

examples.annotated_text: 1973_oil_crisis: Despite being relatively unaffected by the embargo, the UK nonetheless faced an [dblookup('UK', 'Crisis During 1973 Oil Embargo') -> Oil Crisis] oil crisis of its own - a series of strikes by [dblookup('UK', 'Strikes Involved') -> coal miners, railroad workers] coal miners and railroad workers over the winter of 1973–74 became a major factor in the [dblookup('UK', 'Political Change Due to Oil Crisis') -> change of government] change of government. Heath asked the British to heat only one room in their houses over the winter. The UK, Germany, Italy, Switzerland, and Norway banned flying, driving, and boating on Sundays. Sweden rationed gasoline and heating oil. The Netherlands imposed prison sentences for those who used more than their ration of electricity.

examples.annotated_text: Packet_switching: Packet mode communication may be implemented with or without intermediate forwarding nodes ( packet switches or routers). Packets are normally forwarded by intermediate network nodes asynchronously using first-in, first-out buffering, but may be forwarded according to some scheduling discipline for [dblookup('Packet_switching', 'Scheduling Disciplines') -> fair queuing, traffic shaping, differentiated quality of service] fair queuing, traffic shaping, or for differentiated or guaranteed quality of service, such as weighted fair queuing or leaky bucket. In case of a shared physical medium (such as radio or 10BASE5), the packets may be delivered according to a [dblookup('Packet_switching', 'Multiple Access Scheme') -> multiple access scheme] multiple access scheme.

examples.annotated_text: Force: All of the forces in the universe are based on four fundamental interactions. The strong and weak forces are [dblookup('Strong Force', 'Type') -> nuclear forces] nuclear forces that act only at very short distances, and are responsible for the interactions between subatomic particles, including [dblookup('Nuclear Forces', 'Interact With') -> nucleons, compound nuclei] nucleons and compound nuclei. The [dblookup('Electromagnetic Force', 'Acts Between') -> electric charges] electromagnetic force acts between electric charges, and the [dblookup('Gravitational Force', 'Acts Between') -> masses] gravitational force acts between masses. All other forces in nature derive from these four fundamental interactions. For example, [dblookup('Friction', 'Derived From') -> electromagnetic force] friction is a manifestation of the electromagnetic force acting between the atoms of two surfaces, and the Pauli exclusion principle, which does not permit atoms to pass through each other. Similarly, the forces in springs, modeled by [dblookup("Hooke's Law", 'Describes') -> electromagnetic forces and Exclusion Principle] Hooke's law, are the result of electromagnetic forces and the Exclusion Principle acting together to return an object to its equilibrium position. [dblookup('Centrifugal Forces', 'Arise From') -> acceleration of rotating frames of reference] Centrifugal forces are acceleration forces that arise simply from the acceleration of rotating frames of reference.
examples.text: Force: All of the forces in the universe are based on four fundamental interactions. The strong and weak forces are nuclear forces that act only at very short distances, and are responsible for the interactions between subatomic particles, including nucleons and compound nuclei. The electromagnetic force acts between electric charges, and the gravitational force acts between masses. All other forces in nature derive from these four fundamental interactions. For example, friction is a manifestation of the electromagnetic force acting between the atoms of two surfaces, and the Pauli exclusion principle, which does not permit atoms to pass through each other. Similarly, the forces in springs, modeled by Hooke's law, are the result of electromagnetic forces and the Exclusion Principle acting together to return an object to its equilibrium position. Centrifugal forces are acceleration forces that arise simply from the acceleration of rotating frames of reference.:12-11:359

examples.annotated_text: Amazon_rainforest: NASA's CALIPSO satellite has measured the amount of dust transported by wind from the Sahara to the Amazon: an average [dblookup('Sahara Dust Transportation', 'Annual Average Dust Amount') -> 182 million tons] 182 million tons of dust are windblown out of the Sahara each year, at 15 degrees west longitude, across 1,600 miles (2,600 km) over the Atlantic Ocean (some dust falls into the Atlantic), then at [dblookup('Sahara Dust Transportation', 'Longitude End') -> 35 degrees west] 35 degrees West longitude at the eastern coast of South America, 27.7 million tons (15%) of dust fall over the Amazon basin, [dblookup('Sahara Dust Transportation', 'Dust Remaining In Air') -> 132 million tons] 132 million tons of dust remain in the air, [dblookup('Caribbean Sea', 'Annual Dust Fall') -> 43 million tons] 43 million tons of dust are windblown and falls on the Caribbean Sea, past [dblookup('Sahara Dust Transportation', 'Last Measured Longitude') -> 75 degrees west] 75 degrees west longitude.
examples.text: Amazon_rainforest: NASA's CALIPSO satellite has measured the amount of dust transported by wind from the Sahara to the Amazon: an average 182 million tons of dust are windblown out of the Sahara each year, at 15 degrees west longitude, across 1,600 miles (2,600 km) over the Atlantic Ocean (some dust falls into the Atlantic), then at 35 degrees West longitude at the eastern coast of South America, 27.7 million tons (15%) of dust fall over the Amazon basin, 132 million tons of dust remain in the air, 43 million tons of dust are windblown and falls on the Caribbean Sea, past 75 degrees west longitude.

examples.annotated_text: University_of_Chicago: The UChicago Arts program joins academic departments and programs in the Division of the Humanities and the College, as well as professional organizations including [dblookup('University_of_Chicago', 'Affiliated Professional Organizations') -> Court Theatre, Oriental Institute, Smart Museum of Art, Renaissance Society, University of Chicago Presents] the Court Theatre, the Oriental Institute, the Smart Museum of Art, the Renaissance Society, University of Chicago Presents, and student arts organizations. The university has an [dblookup('University_of_Chicago', 'Artists-in-Residence Program') -> Artist-in-Residence Program] artist-in-residence program and scholars in performance studies, contemporary art criticism, and film history. It has offered a [dblookup('University_of_Chicago', 'Doctorate in Music Composition Offered Since') -> 1933] doctorate in music composition since 1933 and in [dblookup('University_of_Chicago', 'Doctorate in Cinema & Media Studies Offered Since') -> 2000] Cinema & Media studies since 2000, a [dblookup('University_of_Chicago', 'Master of Fine Arts in Visual Arts Offered Since') -> early 1970s] master of fine arts in visual arts (early 1970s), and a [dblookup('University_of_Chicago', 'Master of Arts in the Humanities with Creative Writing Track Offered Since') -> 2000] master of arts in the humanities with a creative writing track (2000). It has [dblookup('University_of_Chicago', 'Bachelor\'s Degree Programs') -> Visual Arts, Music, Art History, Cinema & Media Studies, Theater & Performance Studies] bachelor's degree programs in visual arts, music, and art history, and, more recently, Cinema & Media studies (1996) and theater & performance studies (2002). The College's general education core includes a [dblookup('University_of_Chicago', 'General Education Core Requirement in the Arts') -> “Dramatic, Music, and Visual Arts” Requirement] “dramatic, music, and visual arts” requirement, requiring students to study the history of the arts, stage desire, or begin working with sculpture. Several thousand major and non-major undergraduates enroll annually in creative and performing arts classes. UChicago is often considered the birthplace of improvisational comedy as the Compass Players student comedy troupe evolved into [dblookup('Compass Players', 'Evolution Into') -> The Second City Improv Theater Troupe] The Second City improv theater troupe in 1959. The Reva and David Logan Center for the Arts opened in [dblookup('Reva and David Logan Center for the Arts', 'Opening Date') -> October 2012] October 2012, five years after a [dblookup('Reva and David Logan Center for the Arts', 'Gift From') -> David Logan and Reva Logan] $35 million gift from alumnus David Logan and his wife Reva. The center includes spaces for exhibitions, performances, classes, and media production. The Logan Center was designed by [dblookup('Reva and David Logan Center for the Arts', 'Architects') -> Tod Williams, Billie Tsien] Tod Williams and Billie Tsien. This building is actually entirely glass. The brick is a facade designed to keep the glass safe from the wind. The architects later removed sections of the bricks when [dblookup('Reva and David Logan Center for the Arts', 'Architectural Modifications Due To') -> Complaints About Blocked Views] pressure arose in the form of complaints that the views of the city were blocked.
examples.text: University_of_Chicago: The UChicago Arts program joins academic departments and programs in the Division of the Humanities and the College, as well as professional organizations including the Court Theatre, the Oriental Institute, the Smart Museum of Art, the Renaissance Society, University of Chicago Presents, and student arts organizations. The university has an artist-in-residence program and scholars in performance studies, contemporary art criticism, and film history. It has offered a doctorate in music composition since 1933 and in Cinema & Media studies since 2000, a master of fine arts in visual arts (early 1970s), and a master of arts in the humanities with a creative writing track (2000). It has bachelor's degree programs in visual arts, music, and art history, and, more recently, Cinema & Media studies (1996) and theater & performance studies (2002). The College's general education core includes a “dramatic, music, and visual arts” requirement, requiring students to study the history of the arts, stage desire, or begin working with sculpture. Several thousand major and non-major undergraduates enroll annually in creative and performing arts classes. UChicago is often considered the birthplace of improvisational comedy as the Compass Players student comedy troupe evolved into The Second City improv theater troupe in 1959. The Reva and David Logan Center for the Arts opened in October 2012, five years after a $35 million gift from alumnus David Logan and his wife Reva. The center includes spaces for exhibitions, performances, classes, and media production. The Logan Center was designed by Tod Williams and Billie Tsien. This building is actually entirely glass. The brick is a facade designed to keep the glass safe from the wind. The architects later removed sections of the bricks when pressure arose in the form of complaints that the views of the city were blocked.

examples.annotated_text: Pharmacy: The advances made in the Middle East in botany and chemistry led medicine in medieval Islam substantially to develop pharmacology. [dblookup('Muhammad ibn Zakarīya Rāzi', 'Contribution to Pharmacology') -> Promoted medical uses of chemical compounds] Muhammad ibn Zakarīya Rāzi (Rhazes) (865–915), for instance, acted to promote the medical uses of chemical compounds. [dblookup('Abu al-Qasim al-Zahrawi', 'Innovations in Medicine Preparation') -> Pioneered sublimation and distillation] Abu al-Qasim al-Zahrawi (Abulcasis) (936–1013) pioneered the preparation of medicines by sublimation and distillation. His [dblookup('Abu al-Qasim al-Zahrawi', 'Notable Work') -> Liber servitoris] Liber servitoris is of particular interest, as it provides the reader with recipes and explains how to prepare the 'simples' from which were compounded the complex drugs then generally used. [dblookup('Sabur Ibn Sahl', 'Contribution to Pharmacology') -> Initiated pharmacopoeia] Sabur Ibn Sahl (d 869), was, however, the first physician to initiate pharmacopoeia, describing a large variety of drugs and remedies for ailments. [dblookup('Al-Biruni', 'Notable Work on Pharmacology') -> Kitab al-Saydalah] Al-Biruni (973–1050) wrote one of the most valuable Islamic works on pharmacology, entitled Kitab al-Saydalah (The Book of Drugs), in which he detailed the properties of drugs and outlined the role of pharmacy and the functions and duties of the pharmacist. [dblookup('Avicenna', 'Contribution to Pharmacology') -> Described 700 drug preparations in The Canon of Medicine] Avicenna, too, described no less than 700 preparations, their properties, modes of action, and their indications. He devoted in fact a whole volume to simple drugs in The Canon of Medicine. Of great impact were also the works by [dblookup('Al-Maridini', 'Impact of Works') -> Widely printed in Latin] al-Maridini of Baghdad and Cairo, and [dblookup('Ibn al-Wafid', 'Works') -> De Medicinis universalibus et particularibus, Medicamentis simplicibus] Ibn al-Wafid (1008–1074), both of which were printed in Latin more than fifty times, appearing as De Medicinis universalibus et particularibus by 'Mesue' the younger, and the Medicamentis simplicibus by 'Abenguefit'. [dblookup('Peter of Abano', 'Translation Work') -> Translated al-Maridini's work as De Veneris] Peter of Abano (1250–1316) translated and added a supplement to the work of al-Maridini under the title De Veneris. [dblookup('Al-Muwaffaq', 'Pioneering Contributions') -> Described arsenious oxide, distinguished sodium carbonate and potassium carbonate] Al-Muwaffaq’s contributions in the field are also pioneering. Living in the 10th century, he wrote The foundations of the true properties of Remedies, amongst others describing arsenious oxide, and being acquainted with silicic acid. He made clear distinction between sodium carbonate and potassium carbonate, and drew attention to the poisonous nature of copper compounds, especially copper vitriol, and also lead compounds. He also describes the distillation of sea-water for drinking.
examples.text: Pharmacy: The advances made in the Middle East in botany and chemistry led medicine in medieval Islam substantially to develop pharmacology. Muhammad ibn Zakarīya Rāzi (Rhazes) (865–915), for instance, acted to promote the medical uses of chemical compounds. Abu al-Qasim al-Zahrawi (Abulcasis) (936–1013) pioneered the preparation of medicines by sublimation and distillation. His Liber servitoris is of particular interest, as it provides the reader with recipes and explains how to prepare the `simples’ from which were compounded the complex drugs then generally used. Sabur Ibn Sahl (d 869), was, however, the first physician to initiate pharmacopoedia, describing a large variety of drugs and remedies for ailments. Al-Biruni (973–1050) wrote one of the most valuable Islamic works on pharmacology, entitled Kitab al-Saydalah (The Book of Drugs), in which he detailed the properties of drugs and outlined the role of pharmacy and the functions and duties of the pharmacist. Avicenna, too, described no less than 700 preparations, their properties, modes of action, and their indications. He devoted in fact a whole volume to simple drugs in The Canon of Medicine. Of great impact were also the works by al-Maridini of Baghdad and Cairo, and Ibn al-Wafid (1008–1074), both of which were printed in Latin more than fifty times, appearing as De Medicinis universalibus et particularibus by 'Mesue' the younger, and the Medicamentis simplicibus by 'Abenguefit'. Peter of Abano (1250–1316) translated and added a supplement to the work of al-Maridini under the title De Veneris. Al-Muwaffaq’s contributions in the field are also pioneering. Living in the 10th century, he wrote The foundations of the true properties of Remedies, amongst others describing arsenious oxide, and being acquainted with silicic acid. He made clear distinction between sodium carbonate and potassium carbonate, and drew attention to the poisonous nature of copper compounds, especially copper vitriol, and also lead compounds. He also describes the distillation of sea-water for drinking.[verification needed]

examples.annotated_text: Normans: The [dblookup('French Wars of Religion', 'Century Occurred') -> 16th century] French Wars of Religion in the 16th century and [dblookup('French Revolution', 'Century Occurred') -> 18th century] French Revolution in the 18th century successively destroyed much of what existed in the way of the architectural and artistic remnant of this Norman creativity. The former, with their [dblookup('French Wars of Religion', 'Effect on Norman Heritage') -> wanton destruction of many Norman edifices] violence, caused the wanton destruction of many Norman edifices; the latter, with its [dblookup('French Revolution', 'Effect on Religious Heritage') -> purposeful destruction of religious objects] assault on religion, caused the purposeful destruction of religious objects of any type, and its destabilisation of society resulted in [dblookup('French Revolution', 'Effect on Society') -> rampant pillaging] rampant pillaging.
examples.text: Normans: The French Wars of Religion in the 16th century and French Revolution in the 18th successively destroyed much of what existed in the way of the architectural and artistic remnant of this Norman creativity. The former, with their violence, caused the wanton destruction of many Norman edifices; the latter, with its assault on religion, caused the purposeful destruction of religious objects of any type, and its destabilisation of society resulted in rampant pillaging.

examples.annotated_text: European_Union_law: None of the original treaties [dblookup('European Union', 'Original Treaties Mention of Fundamental Rights') -> No] establishing the European Union mention protection for fundamental rights. It was not envisaged for European Union measures, that is legislative and administrative actions by European Union institutions, to be subject to human rights. At the time the only concern was that member states should be prevented from violating human rights, hence the establishment of the [dblookup('European Convention on Human Rights', 'Established In') -> 1950] European Convention on Human Rights in 1950 and the establishment of the European Court of Human Rights. The European Court of Justice recognised [dblookup('European Court of Justice', 'Recognition') -> Fundamental rights as general principle of EU law] fundamental rights as general principle of European Union law as the need to ensure that European Union measures are compatible with the human rights enshrined in member states' constitution became ever more apparent. In 1999 the European Council set up a body tasked with drafting a European Charter of Human Rights, which could form the constitutional basis for the European Union and as such tailored specifically to apply to the European Union and its institutions. The Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union draws a list of fundamental rights from these sources.
examples.text: European_Union_law: None of the original treaties establishing the European Union mention protection for fundamental rights. It was not envisaged for European Union measures, that is legislative and administrative actions by European Union institutions, to be subject to human rights. At the time the only concern was that member states should be prevented from violating human rights, hence the establishment of the European Convention on Human Rights in 1950 and the establishment of the European Court of Human Rights. The European Court of Justice recognised fundamental rights as general principle of European Union law as the need to ensure that European Union measures are compatible with the human rights enshrined in member states' constitution became ever more apparent. In 1999 the European Council set up a body tasked with drafting a European Charter of Human Rights, which could form the constitutional basis for the European Union and as such tailored specifically to apply to the European Union and its institutions. The Charter of Fundamental Rights of the European Union draws a list of fundamental rights from the European Convention on Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms, the Declaration on Fundamental Rights produced by the European Parliament in 1989 and European Union Treaties.

examples.annotated_text: European_Union_law: The [dblookup('European Commission', 'Role') -> main executive body of the European Union] European Commission is the main executive body of the European Union. Article 17(1) of the Treaty on European Union states the Commission should "promote the general interest of the Union" while Article 17(3) adds that [dblookup('European Commission', 'Independence Requirement') -> Commissioners should be completely independent] Commissioners should be "completely independent" and not "take instructions from any Government". Under article 17(2), [dblookup('European Commission', 'Legislative Monopoly') -> monopoly on initiating the legislative procedure] "Union legislative acts may only be adopted on the basis of a Commission proposal, except where the Treaties provide otherwise." This means that the Commission has a monopoly on initiating the legislative procedure, although the Council is the [dblookup('Council of the European Union', 'Legislative Role') -> de facto catalyst of many legislative initiatives] "de facto catalyst of many legislative initiatives". The Parliament can also formally request the Commission to submit a legislative proposal but the commission can reject such a suggestion, giving reasons. The [dblookup('President of the European Commission', 'Role') -> sets the agenda for the EU's work] Commission's President (currently an ex-Luxembourg Prime Minister, Jean-Claude Juncker) sets the agenda for the EU's work. Since Ireland refused to consent to changes in the Treaty of Lisbon 2007, there remains [dblookup('European Commission', 'Number of Commissioners') -> one Commissioner for each of the 28 member states] one Commissioner for each of the 28 member states, including the President and the High Representative for Foreign and Security Policy (currently [dblookup('Federica Mogherini', 'Position') -> High Representative for Foreign and Security Policy] Federica Mogherini). The proposal to make the Commissioners be drawn from the elected Parliament, was not adopted in the Treaty of Lisbon. This means Commissioners are, through the appointment process, the unelected subordinates of member state governments.
examples.text: European_Union_law: The European Commission is the main executive body of the European Union. Article 17(1) of the Treaty on European Union states the Commission should "promote the general interest of the Union" while Article 17(3) adds that Commissioners should be "completely independent" and not "take instructions from any Government". Under article 17(2), "Union legislative acts may only be adopted on the basis of a Commission proposal, except where the Treaties provide otherwise." This means that the Commission has a monopoly on initiating the legislative procedure, although the Council is the "de facto catalyst of many legislative initiatives". The Parliament can also formally request the Commission to submit a legislative proposal but the Commission can reject such a suggestion, giving reasons. The Commission's President (currently an ex-Luxembourg Prime Minister, Jean-Claude Juncker) sets the agenda for the EU's work. Decisions are taken by a simple majority vote, usually through a "written procedure" of circulating the proposals and adopting if there are no objections.[citation needed] Since Ireland refused to consent to changes in the Treaty of Lisbon 2007, there remains one Commissioner for each of the 28 member states, including the President and the High Representative for Foreign and Security Policy (currently Federica Mogherini). The Commissioners (and most importantly, the portfolios they will hold) are bargained over intensively by the member states. The Commissioners, as a block, are then subject to a qualified majority vote of the Council to approve, and majority approval of the Parliament. The proposal to make the Commissioners be drawn from the elected Parliament, was not adopted in the Treaty of Lisbon. This means Commissioners are, through the appointment process, the unelected subordinates of member state governments.

examples.annotated_text: Economic_inequality: Crime rate has also been shown to be [dblookup('Crime Rate', 'Correlation With') -> inequality in society] correlated with inequality in society. Most studies looking into the relationship have concentrated on homicides – since homicides are almost identically defined across all nations and jurisdictions. There have been over fifty studies showing tendencies for violence to be more common in societies where income differences are larger. [dblookup('Daly et al. 2001', 'Findings') -> tenfold difference in U.S. and Canadian homicide rates related to inequality] Daly et al. 2001 found that among U.S States and Canadian Provinces there is a tenfold difference in homicide rates related to inequality. They estimated that about [dblookup('Homicide Rate Variation', 'Attributed To Inequality Differences') -> half] half of all variation in homicide rates can be accounted for by differences in the amount of inequality in each province or state. [dblookup('Fajnzylber et al. 2002', 'Findings') -> worldwide relationship between homicides and inequality] Fajnzylber et al. (2002) found a similar relationship worldwide.
examples.text: Economic_inequality: Crime rate has also been shown to be correlated with inequality in society. Most studies looking into the relationship have concentrated on homicides – since homicides are almost identically defined across all nations and jurisdictions. There have been over fifty studies showing tendencies for violence to be more common in societies where income differences are larger. Research has been conducted comparing developed countries with undeveloped countries, as well as studying areas within countries. Daly et al. 2001 found that among U.S States and Canadian Provinces there is a tenfold difference in homicide rates related to inequality. They estimated that about half of all variation in homicide rates can be accounted for by differences in the amount of inequality in each province or state. Fajnzylber et al. examples.annotated_text: Force: The pound-force has a metric counterpart, less commonly used than the newton: the kilogram-force (kgf) (sometimes kilopond), is the [dblookup('Kilogram-force', 'Force Exerted By') -> standard gravity on one kilogram] force exerted by standard gravity on one kilogram of mass. The kilogram-force leads to an alternate, but rarely used unit of mass: the metric slug (sometimes mug or hyl) is that mass that accelerates at 1 m·s−2 when subjected to a force of 1 kgf. The [dblookup('Kilogram-force', 'Inclusion In SI System') -> not part] kilogram-force is not a part of the modern SI system, and is generally deprecated; however, it still sees use for some purposes as expressing aircraft weight, jet thrust, bicycle spoke tension, torque wrench settings, and engine output torque. Other arcane units of force include the sthène, which is equivalent to 1000 N, and the [dblookup('Kip', 'Equivalent Force') -> 1000 lbf] kip, which is equivalent to 1000 lbf.

examples.annotated_text: Immune_system: Immunology is a science that examines the [dblookup('Immunology', 'Focus') -> structure and function of the immune system] structure and function of the immune system. It originates from [dblookup('Immunology', 'Originated From') -> medicine] medicine and early studies on the causes of immunity to disease. The earliest known reference to immunity was during the [dblookup('Immunity', 'Earliest Known Reference') -> plague of Athens in 430 BC] plague of Athens in 430 BC. Thucydides noted that people who had recovered from a previous bout of the disease could nurse the sick without contracting the illness a second time. In the 18th century, [dblookup('Pierre-Louis Moreau de Maupertuis', 'Experiments With') -> scorpion venom] Pierre-Louis Moreau de Maupertuis made experiments with scorpion venom and observed that certain dogs and mice were immune to this venom. This and other observations of acquired immunity were later exploited by Louis Pasteur in his development of vaccination and his [dblookup('Louis Pasteur', 'Proposed Theory') -> germ theory of disease] proposed germ theory of disease. Pasteur's theory was in direct opposition to contemporary theories of disease, such as the [dblookup('Miasma Theory', 'Opposed By') -> germ theory of disease] miasma theory. It was not until Robert Koch's 1891 proofs, for which he was awarded a [dblookup('Robert Koch', 'Nobel Prize Year') -> 1905] Nobel Prize in 1905, that microorganisms were confirmed as the cause of infectious disease. Viruses were confirmed as human pathogens with the discovery of the yellow fever virus by [dblookup('Yellow Fever Virus', 'Discovered By') -> Walter Reed] Walter Reed.
examples.text: Immune_system: Immunology is a science that examines the structure and function of the immune system. It originates from medicine and early studies on the causes of immunity to disease. The earliest known reference to immunity was during the plague of Athens in 430 BC. Thucydides noted that people who had recovered from a previous bout of the disease could nurse the sick without contracting the illness a second time. In the 18th century, Pierre-Louis Moreau de Maupertuis made experiments with scorpion venom and observed that certain dogs and mice were immune to this venom. This and other observations of acquired immunity were later exploited by Louis Pasteur in his development of vaccination and his proposed germ theory of disease. Pasteur's theory was in direct opposition to contemporary theories of disease, such as the miasma theory. It was not until Robert Koch's 1891 proofs, for which he was awarded a Nobel Prize in 1905, that microorganisms were confirmed as the cause of infectious disease. Viruses were confirmed as human pathogens in 1901, with the discovery of the yellow fever virus by Walter Reed.

examples.annotated_text: Computational_complexity_theory: To measure the difficulty of solving a computational problem, one may wish to see how much time the best algorithm requires to solve the problem. However, the running time may, in general, depend on the instance. In particular, [dblookup('Computational Problem', 'Instance Size Dependency') -> larger instances require more time] larger instances will require more time to solve. Thus the time required to solve a problem (or the space required, or any measure of complexity) is calculated as a [dblookup('Computational Complexity', 'Function Of') -> size of the instance] function of the size of the instance. This is usually taken to be the [dblookup('Input Size', 'Measurement') -> size of input in bits] size of the input in bits. Complexity theory is interested in [dblookup('Complexity Theory', 'Focus Area') -> scalability of algorithms with input size] how algorithms scale with an increase in the input size. For instance, in the problem of finding whether a graph is connected, [dblookup('Graph Connectivity Problem', 'Complexity Measure') -> time comparison for 2n vs. n vertices] how much more time does it take to solve a problem for a graph with 2n vertices compared to the time taken for a graph with n vertices?
examples.text: Computational_complexity_theory: To measure the difficulty of solving a computational problem, one may wish to see how much time the best algorithm requires to solve the problem. However, the running time may, in general, depend on the instance. In particular, larger instances will require more time to solve. Thus the time required to solve a problem (or the space required, or any measure of complexity) is calculated as a function of the size of the instance. This is usually taken to be the size of the input in bits. Complexity theory is interested in how algorithms scale with an increase in the input size. For instance, in the problem of finding whether a graph is connected, how much more time does it take to solve a problem for a graph with 2n vertices compared to the time taken for a graph with n vertices?

examples.annotated_text: Imperialism: The [dblookup('Ottoman Empire', 'Formed In') -> 1299] Ottoman Empire was an imperial state that lasted from 1299 to [dblookup('Ottoman Empire', 'Dissolution') -> 1923] 1923. During the 16th and 17th centuries, in particular at the height of its power under the [dblookup('Ottoman Empire', 'Height of Power Ruler') -> Suleiman the Magnificent] reign of Suleiman the Magnificent, the Ottoman Empire was a powerful [dblookup('Ottoman Empire', 'Empire Characteristics') -> multinational, multilingual] multinational, multilingual empire controlling much of [dblookup('Ottoman Empire', 'Territorial Extent') -> Southeast Europe, Western Asia, the Caucasus, North Africa, Horn of Africa] Southeast Europe, Western Asia, the Caucasus, North Africa, and the Horn of Africa. At the beginning of the 17th century, the empire contained [dblookup('Ottoman Empire', 'Provinces at 17th Century Start') -> 32] 32 provinces and numerous vassal states. Some of these were later absorbed into the empire, while others were granted various types of autonomy during the course of centuries.
examples.text: Imperialism: The Ottoman Empire was an imperial state that lasted from 1299 to 1923. During the 16th and 17th centuries, in particular at the height of its power under the reign of Suleiman the Magnificent, the Ottoman Empire was a powerful multinational, multilingual empire controlling much of Southeast Europe, Western Asia, the Caucasus, North Africa, and the Horn of Africa. At the beginning of the 17th century the empire contained 32 provinces and numerous vassal states. Some of these were later absorbed into the empire, while others were granted various types of autonomy during the course of centuries.

examples.annotated_text: French_and_Indian_War: Jacques Legardeur de Saint-Pierre, who succeeded Marin as commander of the [dblookup('Jacques Legardeur de Saint-Pierre', 'Command') -> French forces] French forces after the latter died on [dblookup('Marin', 'Death Date') -> October 29] October 29, invited [dblookup('George Washington', 'Invited To Dine By') -> Jacques Legardeur de Saint-Pierre] Washington to dine with him. Over dinner, Washington presented Saint-Pierre with the [dblookup('George Washington', 'Delivered Letter From') -> Dinwiddie] letter from Dinwiddie demanding an immediate French withdrawal from the Ohio Country. Saint-Pierre said, "As to the Summons you send me to retire, I do not think myself obliged to obey it." He told Washington that France's claim to the region was superior to that of the British, since René-Robert Cavelier, Sieur de La Salle had explored the Ohio Country nearly a century earlier.
examples.text: French_and_Indian_War: Jacques Legardeur de Saint-Pierre, who succeeded Marin as commander of the French forces after the latter died on October 29, invited Washington to dine with him. examples.annotated_text: Geology: In addition to identifying rocks in the field, [dblookup('Petrologists', 'Laboratory Role') -> identify rock samples] petrologists identify rock samples in the laboratory. Two of the primary methods for identifying rocks in the laboratory are through [dblookup('Rock Identification Methods', 'Laboratory Techniques') -> optical microscopy, electron microprobe] optical microscopy and by using an electron microprobe. In an [dblookup('Optical Microscopy', 'Analysis Type') -> optical mineralogy analysis] optical mineralogy analysis, thin sections of rock samples are analyzed through a [dblookup('Optical Mineralogy', 'Instrument Used') -> petrographic microscope] petrographic microscope, where the minerals can be identified through their different properties in plane-polarized and cross-polarized light, including [dblookup('Mineral Identification Properties', 'Observed Properties') -> birefringence, pleochroism, twinning, interference properties] their birefringence, pleochroism, twinning, and interference properties with a conoscopic lens. In the [dblookup('Electron Microprobe', 'Purpose') -> chemical composition analysis] electron microprobe, individual locations are analyzed for their exact chemical compositions and variation in composition within individual crystals. Stable and radioactive isotope studies provide insight into the geochemical evolution of rock units.
examples.text: Geology: In addition to identifying rocks in the field, petrologists identify rock samples in the laboratory. Two of the primary methods for identifying rocks in the laboratory are through optical microscopy and by using an electron microprobe. In an optical mineralogy analysis, thin sections of rock samples are analyzed through a petrographic microscope, where the minerals can be identified through their different properties in plane-polarized and cross-polarized light, including their birefringence, pleochroism, twinning, and interference properties with a conoscopic lens. In the electron microprobe, individual locations are analyzed for their exact chemical compositions and variation in composition within individual crystals. Stable and radioactive isotope studies provide insight into the geochemical evolution of rock units.

examples.annotated_text: Amazon_rainforest: For a long time, it was thought that the Amazon rainforest was only ever sparsely populated, due to the poor soil making it impossible to sustain a large population through agriculture. Archeologist [dblookup('Betty Meggers', 'Notable Work') -> Amazonia: Man and Culture in a Counterfeit Paradise] Betty Meggers was a prominent proponent of this idea, as described in her book Amazonia: Man and Culture in a Counterfeit Paradise. She claimed that a population density of 0.2 inhabitants per square kilometre is the maximum that can be sustained in the rainforest through hunting, with agriculture needed to host a larger population. However, recent anthropological findings suggest that some 5 million people may have lived in the Amazon region in AD 1500, divided between dense coastal settlements, such as that at Marajó, and inland dwellers. By [dblookup('Amazon region population', 'Year 1900') -> 1 million] 1900 the population had fallen to 1 million and by the [dblookup('Amazon region population', 'Early 1980s') -> less than 200,000] early 1980s it was less than 200,000.
examples.text: Amazon_rainforest: For a long time, it was thought that the Amazon rainforest was only ever sparsely populated, as it was impossible to sustain a large population through agriculture given the poor soil. Archeologist Betty Meggers was a prominent proponent of this idea, as described in her book Amazonia: Man and Culture in a Counterfeit Paradise. She claimed that a population density of 0.2 inhabitants per square kilometre (0.52/sq mi) is the maximum that can be sustained in the rainforest through hunting, with agriculture needed to host a larger population. However, recent anthropological findings have suggested that the region was actually densely populated. Some 5 million people may have lived in the Amazon region in AD 1500, divided between dense coastal settlements, such as that at Marajó, and inland dwellers. By 1900 the population had fallen to 1 million and by the early 1980s it was less than 200,000.

examples.annotated_text: Rhine: The length of the Rhine is conventionally measured in [dblookup('Rhine', 'Measurement Unit Introduced In') -> 1939] "Rhine-kilometers" (Rheinkilometer), a scale introduced in 1939 which runs from [dblookup('Rhine-kilometers', 'Start Point') -> Old Rhine Bridge at Constance] the Old Rhine Bridge at Constance (0 km) to [dblookup('Rhine-kilometers', 'End Point') -> Hoek van Holland] Hoek van Holland (1036.20 km). The [dblookup('Rhine', 'Length by Rhine-kilometers') -> 1036.20 km] river length is significantly shortened from the river's natural course due to a number of canalisation projects completed in the 19th and 20th century. The "total length of the Rhine", to the inclusion of Lake Constance and the Alpine Rhine, is more difficult to measure objectively; it was cited as [dblookup('Rhine', 'Total Length including Lake Constance and Alpine Rhine') -> 1,232 kilometres (766 miles)] 1,232 kilometres (766 miles) by the Dutch Rijkswaterstaat in 2010.
examples.text: Rhine: The length of the Rhine is conventionally measured in "Rhine-kilometers" (Rheinkilometer), a scale introduced in 1939 which runs from the Old Rhine Bridge at Constance (0 km) to Hoek van Holland (1036.20 km). The river length is significantly shortened from the river's natural course due to number of canalisation projects completed in the 19th and 20th century.[note 7] The "total length of the Rhine", to the inclusion of Lake Constance and the Alpine Rhine is more difficult to measure objectively; it was cited as 1,232 kilometres (766 miles) by the Dutch Rijkswaterstaat in 2010.[note 1]

examples.annotated_text: Immune_system: Chemical barriers also protect against infection. The skin and [dblookup('Respiratory Tract', 'Secretes') -> antimicrobial peptides] respiratory tract secrete antimicrobial peptides such as the β-defensins. [dblookup('Saliva', 'Contains Enzymes') -> lysozyme, phospholipase A2] Enzymes such as lysozyme and phospholipase A2 in saliva, [dblookup('Tears', 'Contains Enzymes') -> lysozyme, phospholipase A2] tears, and [dblookup('Breast Milk', 'Contains Enzymes') -> lysozyme, phospholipase A2] breast milk are also antibacterials. [dblookup('Vaginal Secretions', 'Chemical Barrier Property') -> slightly acidic] Vaginal secretions serve as a chemical barrier following menarche, when they become slightly acidic, while [dblookup('Semen', 'Contains') -> defensins, zinc] semen contains defensins and zinc to kill pathogens. In the stomach, [dblookup('Gastric Acid', 'Function') -> defense against ingested pathogens] gastric acid and [dblookup('Stomach Proteases', 'Function') -> defense against ingested pathogens] proteases serve as powerful chemical defenses against ingested pathogens.
examples.text: Immune_system: Chemical barriers also protect against infection. The skin and respiratory tract secrete antimicrobial peptides such as the β-defensins. Enzymes such as lysozyme and phospholipase A2 in saliva, tears, and breast milk are also antibacterials. Vaginal secretions serve as a chemical barrier following menarche, when they become slightly acidic, while semen contains defensins and zinc to kill pathogens. In the stomach, gastric acid and proteases serve as powerful chemical defenses against ingested pathogens.

examples.annotated_text: Immune_system: Pattern recognition receptors are proteins used by nearly all organisms to identify molecules associated with pathogens. Antimicrobial peptides called [dblookup('Defensins', 'Role In') -> Innate immune response] defensins are an evolutionarily conserved component of the innate immune response found in all animals and plants, and represent the [dblookup('Defensins', 'Significance For Invertebrates') -> Main form of systemic immunity] main form of invertebrate systemic immunity. The [dblookup('Complement system', 'Role In') -> Invertebrate immunity] complement system and [dblookup('Phagocytic cells', 'Role In') -> Invertebrate immunity] phagocytic cells are also used by most forms of invertebrate life. [dblookup('Ribonucleases', 'Role In') -> Eukaryotic immune response to viruses] Ribonucleases and the [dblookup('RNA interference pathway', 'Conservation In') -> All eukaryotes] RNA interference pathway are conserved across all eukaryotes, and are thought to play a role in the immune response to viruses.
examples.text: Immune_system: Pattern recognition receptors are proteins used by nearly all organisms to identify molecules associated with pathogens. Antimicrobial peptides called defensins are an evolutionarily conserved component of the innate immune response found in all animals and plants, and represent the main form of invertebrate systemic immunity. The complement system and phagocytic cells are also used by most forms of invertebrate life. Ribonucleases and the RNA interference pathway are conserved across all eukaryotes, and are thought to play a role in the immune response to viruses.

examples.annotated_text: Amazon_rainforest: Following the [dblookup('Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event', 'Effect On') -> Amazon rainforest] Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event, the extinction of the dinosaurs and the wetter climate may have allowed the tropical rainforest to spread out across the continent. From [dblookup('Amazon rainforest', 'Historical Extent Period') -> 66–34 Mya] 66–34 Mya, the rainforest extended as far south as 45°. Climate fluctuations during the [dblookup('Amazon rainforest', 'Climate Change Impact Period') -> last 34 million years] last 34 million years have allowed savanna regions to expand into the tropics. During the [dblookup('Oligocene', 'Impact On') -> Amazon rainforest] Oligocene, for example, the rainforest spanned a relatively narrow band. It expanded again during the [dblookup('Middle Miocene', 'Impact On') -> Amazon rainforest] Middle Miocene, then retracted to a mostly inland formation at the [dblookup('Last glacial maximum', 'Effect On') -> Amazon rainforest] last glacial maximum. However, the rainforest still managed to thrive during these glacial periods, allowing for the survival and evolution of a [dblookup('Amazon rainforest', 'Species Diversity During Glacial Periods') -> broad diversity of species] broad diversity of species.
examples.text: Amazon_rainforest: Following the Cretaceous–Paleogene extinction event, the extinction of the dinosaurs and the wetter climate may have allowed the tropical rainforest to spread out across the continent. From 66–34 Mya, the rainforest extended as far south as 45°. Climate fluctuations during the last 34 million years have allowed savanna regions to expand into the tropics. During the Oligocene, for example, the rainforest spanned a relatively narrow band. It expanded again during the Middle Miocene, then retracted to a mostly inland formation at the last glacial maximum. However, the rainforest still managed to thrive during these glacial periods, allowing for the survival and evolution of a broad diversity of species.

examples.annotated_text: Rhine: The other third of the water flows through the Pannerdens Kanaal and redistributes in the IJssel and Nederrijn. The [dblookup('IJssel', 'Water Flow Proportion') -> One Ninth] IJssel branch carries one ninth of the water flow of the Rhine north into the IJsselmeer (a former bay), while the Nederrijn carries approximately two ninths of the flow west along a route parallel to the Waal. However, at [dblookup('Wijk bij Duurstede', 'Location Significance') -> Name Change Nederrijn to Lek] Wijk bij Duurstede, the Nederrijn changes its name and becomes the Lek. It flows farther west, to [dblookup('Lek', 'Connection To') -> Noord River, Nieuwe Maas] rejoin the Noord River into the Nieuwe Maas and to the [dblookup('Nieuwe Maas', 'Outflow') -> North Sea] North Sea.
examples.text: Rhine: The other third of the water flows through the Pannerdens Kanaal and redistributes in the IJssel and Nederrijn. The IJssel branch carries one ninth of the water flow of the Rhine north into the IJsselmeer (a former bay), while the Nederrijn carries approximately two ninths of the flow west along a route parallel to the Waal. However, at Wijk bij Duurstede, the Nederrijn changes its name and becomes the Lek. It flows farther west, to rejoin the Noord River into the Nieuwe Maas and to the North Sea.

examples.annotated_text: Rhine: At present, the branches [dblookup('Waal', 'Discharges To') -> North Sea] Waal and [dblookup('Nederrijn-Lek', 'Discharges To') -> North Sea] Nederrijn-Lek discharge to the North Sea, through the former Meuse estuary, near Rotterdam. The river [dblookup('IJssel', 'Flows To') -> IJsselmeer] IJssel branch flows to the north and enters the IJsselmeer, formerly [dblookup('IJsselmeer', 'Former Name') -> Zuider Zee brackish lagoon] the Zuider Zee brackish lagoon; however, since [dblookup('IJsselmeer', 'Freshwater Lake Since') -> 1932] 1932, a freshwater lake. The discharge of the Rhine is divided among three branches: the River [dblookup('River Waal', 'Discharge Fraction') -> 6/9] Waal (6/9 of total discharge), the River [dblookup('River Nederrijn-Lek', 'Discharge Fraction') -> 2/9] Nederrijn – Lek (2/9 of total discharge) and the River [dblookup('River IJssel', 'Discharge Fraction') -> 1/9] IJssel (1/9 of total discharge). This discharge distribution has been maintained since [dblookup('Rhine Discharge Distribution', 'Maintained Since') -> 1709] 1709, by river engineering works, including the digging of the [dblookup('Pannerdens canal', 'River Canal') -> Pannerdens canal] and since the 20th century, with the help of [dblookup('Nederrijn', 'Weirs Used Since Century') -> 20th century] weirs in the Nederrijn river.
examples.text: Rhine: At present, the branches Waal and Nederrijn-Lek discharge to the North Sea, through the former Meuse estuary, near Rotterdam. The river IJssel branch flows to the north and enters the IJsselmeer, formerly the Zuider Zee brackish lagoon; however, since 1932, a freshwater lake. The discharge of the Rhine is divided among three branches: the River Waal (6/9 of total discharge), the River Nederrijn – Lek (2/9 of total discharge) and the River IJssel (1/9 of total discharge). This discharge distribution has been maintained since 1709, by river engineering works, including the digging of the Pannerdens canal and since the 20th century, with the help of weirs in the Nederrijn river.

examples.annotated_text: Geology: [dblookup('Structural Geologists', 'Method Used') -> Microscopic analysis of oriented thin sections] Structural geologists use microscopic analysis of oriented thin sections of geologic samples to observe the fabric within the rocks, which gives information about [dblookup('Structural Geologists', 'Information Gathered About') -> Strain within crystalline structure] strain within the crystalline structure of the rocks. They also [dblookup('Structural Geologists', 'Techniques') -> Plot and combine measurements] plot and combine measurements of geological structures in order to better understand the orientations of faults and folds in order to reconstruct the history of rock deformation in the area. In addition, they perform [dblookup('Structural Geologists', 'Experiments') -> Analog and numerical experiments of rock deformation] analog and numerical experiments of rock deformation in large and small settings.
examples.text: Geology: Structural geologists use microscopic analysis of oriented thin sections of geologic samples to observe the fabric within the rocks which gives information about strain within the crystalline structure of the rocks. They also plot and combine measurements of geological structures in order to better understand the orientations of faults and folds in order to reconstruct the history of rock deformation in the area. In addition, they perform analog and numerical experiments of rock deformation in large and small settings.

examples.annotated_text: Normans: In the course of the 10th century, the initially destructive incursions of Norse war bands into the rivers of France evolved into more permanent encampments that included local women and personal property. examples.text: Normans: In the course of the 10th century, the initially destructive incursions of Norse war bands into the rivers of France evolved into more permanent encampments that included local women and personal property. The Duchy of Normandy, which began in 911 as a fiefdom, was established by the treaty of Saint-Clair-sur-Epte between King Charles III of West Francia and the famed Viking ruler Rollo, and was situated in the former Frankish kingdom of Neustria. The treaty offered Rollo and his men the French lands between the river Epte and the Atlantic coast in exchange for their protection against further Viking incursions. The territory was roughly equivalent to the old province of Rouen, and reproduced the Roman administrative structure of Gallia Lugdunensis II (part of the former Gallia Lugdunensis).

examples.annotated_text: Prime_number: The evolutionary strategy used by cicadas of the genus Magicicada make use of prime numbers. These insects spend most of their lives as grubs underground. They only pupate and then emerge from their burrows after 7, 13, or 17 years, at which point they fly about, breed, and then die after a few weeks at most. The logic for this is believed to be that the prime number intervals between emergences make it very difficult for predators to evolve that could specialize as predators on Magicicadas. If Magicicadas appeared at a non-prime number intervals, say every 12 years, then predators appearing every 2, 3, 4, 6, or 12 years would be sure to meet them. Over a 200-year period, average predator populations during hypothetical outbreaks of 14- and 15-year cicadas would be up to 2% higher than during outbreaks of 13- and 17-year cicadas. Though small, this advantage appears to have been enough to drive natural selection in favour of a [dblookup('Magicicada', 'Life-Cycle Strategy') -> prime-numbered life-cycle] prime-numbered life-cycle for these insects.

Days later, still in 1851 [dblookup('Gold Discovery in Victoria_(Australia)', 'Initial Location') -> Ballarat] gold was discovered near Ballarat, and subsequently [dblookup('Gold Discovery in Victoria_(Australia)', 'Subsequent Location') -> Bendigo] at Bendigo. examples.text: Victoria_(Australia): On 1 July 1851, writs were issued for the election of the first Victorian Legislative Council, and the absolute independence of Victoria from New South Wales was established proclaiming a new Colony of Victoria. Days later, still in 1851 gold was discovered near Ballarat, and subsequently at Bendigo. Later discoveries occurred at many sites across Victoria. examples.annotated_text: Amazon_rainforest: Terra preta (black earth), which is distributed over large areas in the Amazon forest, is now widely accepted as a [dblookup('Terra Preta', 'Origin') -> indigenous soil management] product of indigenous soil management. The development of this fertile soil allowed agriculture and silviculture in the previously hostile environment; meaning that large portions of the Amazon rainforest are probably the result of centuries of [dblookup('Amazon Rainforest', 'Human Influence') -> human management] human management, rather than naturally occurring as has previously been supposed. In the region of the Xingu tribe, remains of some of these large settlements in the middle of the Amazon forest were found in [dblookup('Large Settlements in Amazon', 'Year Discovered') -> 2003] 2003 by [dblookup('Large Settlements in Amazon', 'Discovered By') -> Michael Heckenberger] Michael Heckenberger and colleagues of the [dblookup('Michael Heckenberger', 'Affiliation') -> University of Florida] University of Florida. Among those were evidence of [dblookup('Large Settlements in Amazon', 'Features Discovered') -> roads, bridges, large plazas] roads, bridges and large plazas.
examples.text: Amazon_rainforest: Terra preta (black earth), which is distributed over large areas in the Amazon forest, is now widely accepted as a product of indigenous soil management. examples.annotated_text: Civil_disobedience: Civil disobedients have chosen a variety of different illegal acts. Bedau writes, "There is a whole class of acts, undertaken in the name of civil disobedience, which, even if they were widely practiced, would in themselves constitute hardly more than a nuisance (e.g. trespassing at a nuclear-missile installation)...Such acts are often just a harassment and, at least to the bystander, somewhat inane...The remoteness of the connection between the disobedient act and the objectionable law lays such acts open to the charge of ineffectiveness and absurdity." Bedau also notes, though, that the very harmlessness of such entirely symbolic illegal protests toward public policy goals may serve a propaganda purpose. Some civil disobedients, such as the proprietors of illegal medical cannabis dispensaries and Voice in the Wilderness, which brought medicine to Iraq without the permission of the U.S. Government, directly achieve [dblookup('Voice in the Wilderness', 'Social Goal') -> provision of medication to the sick] a desired social goal (such as the provision of medication to the sick) while openly breaking the law. Julia Butterfly Hill lived in Luna, a 180-foot (55 m)-tall, 600-year-old California Redwood tree for 738 days, successfully preventing it from being cut down.

examples.annotated_text: Oxygen: People who climb mountains or fly in non-pressurized fixed-wing aircraft sometimes have [dblookup('Oxygen', 'Use In Human Activities') -> supplemental O2 supplies] supplemental O2 supplies.[h] Passengers traveling in (pressurized) commercial airplanes have an emergency supply of O2 automatically supplied to them in case of cabin depressurization. Sudden cabin pressure loss activates [dblookup('Commercial Airplanes', 'Safety Equipment') -> Chemical oxygen generators] chemical oxygen generators above each seat, causing oxygen masks to drop. Pulling on the masks "to start the flow of oxygen" as cabin safety instructions dictate, forces iron filings into the [dblookup('Chemical Oxygen Generators', 'Chemical Reaction') -> sodium chlorate reaction] sodium chlorate inside the canister. A steady stream of oxygen gas is then produced by the [dblookup('Chemical Oxygen Generators', 'Reaction Type') -> exothermic reaction] exothermic reaction.

examples.annotated_text: Warsaw: Building activity occurred in numerous noble palaces and churches during the later decades of the [dblookup('Warsaw', 'Significant Architectural Period') -> 17th century] 17th century. The most impressive examples of rococo architecture are [dblookup('Czapski Palace', 'Construction Period') -> 1712–1721] Czapski Palace (1712–1721), [dblookup('Palace of the Four Winds', 'Construction Period') -> 1730s] Palace of the Four Winds (1730s) and [dblookup('Visitationist Church', 'Façade Construction Period') -> 1728–1761] Visitationist Church (façade 1728–1761). examples.annotated_text: Computational_complexity_theory: Closely related fields in theoretical computer science are [dblookup('Computational Complexity Theory', 'Related Fields') -> Analysis of Algorithms, Computability Theory] analysis of algorithms and computability theory. A key distinction between analysis of algorithms and computational complexity theory is that the former is devoted to analyzing the amount of resources needed by a particular algorithm to solve a problem, whereas the latter asks a more general question about all possible algorithms that could be used to solve the same problem. More precisely, it tries to classify problems that can or cannot be solved with appropriately restricted resources. In turn, imposing restrictions on the available resources is what distinguishes [dblookup('Computational Complexity Theory', 'Differentiated By') -> Restricted Resources] computational complexity from computability theory: the latter theory asks what kind of problems can, in principle, be solved algorithmically.

examples.annotated_text: European_Union_law: The principal Treaties that form the European Union began with [dblookup('European Union', 'Initial Focus Areas') -> coal, steel, atomic energy] common rules for coal and steel, and then atomic energy, but more complete and formal institutions were established through the [dblookup('European Union', 'Foundational Treaty') -> Treaty of Rome 1957] Treaty of Rome 1957 and the [dblookup('European Union', 'Foundational Treaty') -> Maastricht Treaty 1992] Maastricht Treaty 1992 (now: TFEU). examples.text: European_Union_law: The principal Treaties that form the European Union began with common rules for coal and steel, and then atomic energy, but more complete and formal institutions were established through the Treaty of Rome 1957 and the Maastricht Treaty 1992 (now: TFEU). Greenland signed a Treaty in 1985 giving it a special status.

examples.annotated_text: Force: Historically, forces were first quantitatively investigated in conditions of static equilibrium where several forces canceled each other out. Such experiments demonstrate the crucial properties that forces are additive vector quantities: they have magnitude and direction. When two forces act on a point particle, the resulting force, the resultant (also called the net force), can be determined by following the parallelogram rule of vector addition: the addition of two vectors represented by sides of a parallelogram gives an equivalent resultant vector that is equal in magnitude and direction to the transversal of the parallelogram. The magnitude of the resultant varies from the difference of the magnitudes of the two forces to their sum, depending on the angle between their lines of action. However, if the forces are acting on an extended body, their respective lines of application must also be specified in order to account for their effects on the motion of the body.

examples.annotated_text: Since the IPCC does not carry out its own research, it operates on the basis of scientific papers and independently documented results from other scientific bodies, and its schedule for producing reports requires a deadline for submissions prior to the report's final release. In principle, this means that any significant new evidence or events that change our understanding of climate science between this deadline and publication of an IPCC report cannot be included. In an area of science where our scientific understanding is rapidly changing, this has been raised as a serious shortcoming in a body which is widely regarded as [dblookup('Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change', 'Reputation') -> Ultimate authority on climate science] the ultimate authority on the science. However, there has generally been a steady evolution of key findings and levels of scientific confidence from one assessment report to the next.[citation needed]

examples.annotated_text: Oxygen: [dblookup('Paleoclimatologists', 'Study') -> oxygen-18 to oxygen-16 ratio] Paleoclimatologists measure the ratio of oxygen-18 and oxygen-16 in the shells and skeletons of marine organisms to determine what the climate was like millions of years ago (see [dblookup('Oxygen', 'Isotope Study Cycle') -> oxygen isotope ratio cycle] oxygen isotope ratio cycle). Seawater molecules that contain the lighter isotope, [dblookup('Oxygen', 'Lighter Isotope') -> oxygen-16] oxygen-16, evaporate at a slightly faster rate than water molecules containing the 12% heavier [dblookup('Oxygen', 'Heavier Isotope') -> oxygen-18] oxygen-18; this disparity increases at lower temperatures. During periods of [dblookup('Global Temperature', 'Effect on Precipitation Oxygen Ratio') -> lower] lower global temperatures, snow and rain from that evaporated water tends to be higher in oxygen-16, and the seawater left behind tends to be [dblookup('Seawater', 'Oxygen Ratio at Lower Temperatures') -> higher in oxygen-18] higher in oxygen-18. Marine organisms then [dblookup('Marine Organisms', 'Oxygen Isotope Incorporation') -> more oxygen-18 at lower temperatures] incorporate more oxygen-18 into their skeletons and shells than they would in a warmer climate. Paleoclimatologists also [dblookup('Paleoclimatologists', 'Direct Measurement Source') -> ice core samples] directly measure this ratio in the water molecules of ice core samples that are up to several hundreds of thousands of years old.
examples.text: Oxygen: Paleoclimatologists measure the ratio of oxygen-18 and oxygen-16 in the shells and skeletons of marine organisms to determine what the climate was like millions of years ago (see oxygen isotope ratio cycle). Seawater molecules that contain the lighter isotope, oxygen-16, evaporate at a slightly faster rate than water molecules containing the 12% heavier oxygen-18; this disparity increases at lower temperatures. During periods of lower global temperatures, snow and rain from that evaporated water tends to be higher in oxygen-16, and the seawater left behind tends to be higher in oxygen-18. Marine organisms then incorporate more oxygen-18 into their skeletons and shells than they would in a warmer climate. Paleoclimatologists also directly measure this ratio in the water molecules of ice core samples that are up to several hundreds of thousands of years old.

examples.annotated_text: Economic_inequality: During the mass high school education movement from 1910–1940, there was an increase in skilled workers, which led to a decrease in the price of skilled labor. High school education during the period was designed to equip students with necessary skill sets to be able to perform at work. In fact, it differs from the present high school education, which is regarded as a stepping-stone to acquire college and advanced degrees. This decrease in wages caused a period of compression and decreased inequality between skilled and unskilled workers. Education is very important for the growth of the economy, however educational inequality in gender also influences the economy. Lagerlof and Galor stated that [dblookup('Gender Inequality in Education', 'Impact on Economic Growth') -> low economic growth] gender inequality in education can result in low economic growth, and continued gender inequality in education, thus creating a [dblookup('Gender Inequality in Education', 'Consequence') -> poverty trap] poverty trap. It is suggested that a large [dblookup('Gap in Male and Female Education', 'Implication') -> backwardness, lower economic growth] gap in male and female education may indicate backwardness and so may be associated with lower economic growth, which can explain why there is economic inequality between countries.

examples.annotated_text: Immune_system: Microorganisms or toxins that successfully enter an organism encounter the cells and mechanisms of the [dblookup('Immune System', 'Component') -> Innate Immune System] innate immune system. The innate response is usually triggered when microbes are identified by [dblookup('Innate Immune System', 'Detection Mechanism') -> pattern recognition receptors] pattern recognition receptors, which recognize components that are conserved among broad groups of microorganisms, or when damaged, injured, or stressed cells send out alarm signals, many of which (but not all) are recognized by the same receptors as those that recognize pathogens. Innate immune defenses are [dblookup('Innate Immune System', 'Specificity Type') -> non-specific] non-specific, meaning these systems respond to pathogens in a generic way. This system does not confer [dblookup('Innate Immune System', 'Long-term Immunity Offer') -> No] long-lasting immunity against a pathogen. The innate immune system is the [dblookup('Innate Immune System', 'Dominance in Host Defense') -> dominant system] dominant system of host defense in most organisms.
