examples.annotated_text: Immune_system: Newborn infants have no prior exposure to microbes and are particularly vulnerable to infection. Several layers of passive protection are provided by the mother. During pregnancy, a particular type of antibody, called [dblookup('Antibody', 'Type Transferred During Pregnancy') -> IgG] IgG, is transported from mother to baby directly across the placenta, so human babies have high levels of antibodies even at birth, with the same range of antigen specificities as their mother. Breast milk or [dblookup('Breast Milk', 'Contains Antibodies') -> Colostrum] colostrum also contains antibodies that are transferred to the gut of the infant and protect against bacterial infections until the newborn can synthesize its own antibodies. This is passive immunity because the fetus does not actually make any memory cells or antibodies—it only borrows them. This passive immunity is usually [dblookup('Passive Immunity', 'Duration') -> Short-term, lasting from a few days up to several months] short-term, lasting from a few days up to several months. In medicine, protective [dblookup('Passive Immunity', 'Artificial Transfer Method') -> Antibody-rich serum] passive immunity can also be transferred artificially from one individual to another via antibody-rich serum.
examples.text: Immune_system: Newborn infants have no prior exposure to microbes and are particularly vulnerable to infection. Several layers of passive protection are provided by the mother. During pregnancy, a particular type of antibody, called IgG, is transported from mother to baby directly across the placenta, so human babies have high levels of antibodies even at birth, with the same range of antigen specificities as their mother. Breast milk or colostrum also contains antibodies that are transferred to the gut of the infant and protect against bacterial infections until the newborn can synthesize its own antibodies. This is passive immunity because the fetus does not actually make any memory cells or antibodies—it only borrows them. This passive immunity is usually short-term, lasting from a few days up to several months. In medicine, protective passive immunity can also be transferred artificially from one individual to another via antibody-rich serum.

examples.annotated_text: Ctenophora: Almost all ctenophores are predators – there are [dblookup('Ctenophora', 'Vegetarian Species') -> none] no vegetarians and only [dblookup('Ctenophora', 'Partly Parasitic Genus') -> one genus] one genus that is partly parasitic. If food is plentiful, [dblookup('Ctenophora', 'Daily Food Consumption Relative to Weight') -> 10 times their own weight] they can eat 10 times their own weight per day. While [dblookup('Beroe', 'Prey') -> other ctenophores] Beroe preys mainly on other ctenophores, other surface-water species prey on [dblookup('Ctenophora', 'Surface-Water Species Prey') -> zooplankton] zooplankton (planktonic animals) ranging in size from the microscopic, including mollusc and fish larvae, to small adult crustaceans such as copepods, amphipods, and even krill. Members of the genus [dblookup('Haeckelia', 'Prey') -> jellyfish] Haeckelia prey on jellyfish and incorporate their prey's nematocysts (stinging cells) into their own tentacles instead of colloblasts. Ctenophores have been compared to spiders in their wide range of techniques from capturing prey – some hang motionless in the water using their tentacles as "webs", some are ambush predators like Salticid jumping spiders, and some dangle a sticky droplet at the end of a fine thread, as bolas spiders do. This variety explains the [dblookup('Ctenophora', 'Body Forms Variety Explanation') -> wide range of predation techniques] wide range of body forms in a phylum with rather few species. The two-tentacled ["cydippid" Lampea](dblookup('Lampea', 'Diet')) -> salps] Lampea feeds exclusively on salps, close relatives of sea-squirts that form large chain-like floating colonies, and juveniles of Lampea attach themselves like parasites to salps that are too large for them to swallow. Members of the cydippid genus [dblookup('Pleurobrachia', 'Prey Specialization') -> strong swimmers like adult copepods] Pleurobrachia and the lobate Bolinopsis often reach high population densities at the same place and time because they specialize in different types of prey: Pleurobrachia's long tentacles mainly capture relatively strong swimmers such as adult copepods, while [dblookup('Bolinopsis', 'Prey Specialization') -> smaller, weaker swimmers like rotifers] Bolinopsis generally feeds on smaller, weaker swimmers such as rotifers and mollusc and crustacean larvae.
examples.text: Ctenophora: Almost all ctenophores are predators – there are no vegetarians and only one genus that is partly parasitic. If food is plentiful, they can eat 10 times their own weight per day. While Beroe preys mainly on other ctenophores, other surface-water species prey on zooplankton (planktonic animals) ranging in size from the microscopic, including mollusc and fish larvae, to small adult crustaceans such as copepods, amphipods, and even krill. Members of the genus Haeckelia prey on jellyfish and incorporate their prey's nematocysts (stinging cells) into their own tentacles instead of colloblasts. Ctenophores have been compared to spiders in their wide range of techniques from capturing prey – some hang motionless in the water using their tentacles as "webs", some are ambush predators like Salticid jumping spiders, and some dangle a sticky droplet at the end of a fine thread, as bolas spiders do. This variety explains the wide range of body forms in a phylum with rather few species. The two-tentacled "cydippid" Lampea feeds exclusively on salps, close relatives of sea-squirts that form large chain-like floating colonies, and juveniles of Lampea attach themselves like parasites to salps that are too large for them to swallow. Members of the cydippid genus Pleurobrachia and the lobate Bolinopsis often reach high population densities at the same place and time because they specialize in different types of prey: Pleurobrachia's long tentacles mainly capture relatively strong swimmers such as adult copepods, while Bolinopsis generally feeds on smaller, weaker swimmers such as rotifers and mollusc and crustacean larvae.

examples.annotated_text: Oxygen: In the triplet form, O2 molecules are paramagnetic. That is, they impart magnetic character to oxygen when it is in the presence of a magnetic field, because of the spin magnetic moments of the unpaired electrons in the molecule, and the negative exchange energy between neighboring O2 molecules. Liquid oxygen is attracted to a magnet to a sufficient extent that, in laboratory demonstrations, a bridge of liquid oxygen may be supported against its own weight between the poles of a powerful magnet.

examples.text: Packet_switching: The CYCLADES packet switching network was a French research network designed and directed by Louis Pouzin. The researcher used a combination of [dblookup('Research Methods', 'Tatiana Kuplich Used') -> Synthetic aperture radar (SAR), Thematic Mapper (TM)] Synthetic aperture radar (SAR) and Thematic Mapper (TM) to accurately place the different portions of the Amazon into one of the four classifications.

examples.annotated_text: Rhine: The shape of the Rhine delta is determined by two bifurcations: first, at [dblookup('Millingen aan de Rijn', 'Geographical Feature Affected') -> Rhine] Millingen aan de Rijn, the Rhine splits into [dblookup('Rhine', 'Branch At Millingen aan de Rijn') -> Waal, Pannerdens Kanaal] Waal and Pannerdens Kanaal, which changes its name to [dblookup('Pannerdens Kanaal', 'Renamed To') -> Nederrijn] Nederrijn at Angeren, and second near Arnhem, the [dblookup('Nederrijn', 'Branch At Arnhem') -> IJssel] IJssel branches off from the Nederrijn. This creates three main flows, two of which change names rather often. The largest and southern main branch begins as [dblookup('Largest Southern Branch', 'Initial Name') -> Waal] Waal and continues as [dblookup('Waal', 'Name Changes') -> Boven Merwede, Beneden Merwede, Noord River, Nieuwe Maas, Het Scheur, Nieuwe Waterweg] Boven Merwede ("Upper Merwede"), Beneden Merwede ("Lower Merwede"), Noord River ("North River"), Nieuwe Maas ("New Meuse"), Het Scheur ("the Rip") and Nieuwe Waterweg ("New Waterway"). The middle flow begins as [dblookup('Middle Flow', 'Initial Name') -> Nederrijn] Nederrijn, then changes into [dblookup('Nederrijn', 'Renamed To') -> Lek] Lek, then joins the [dblookup('Lek', 'Confluence With') -> Noord] Noord, thereby forming Nieuwe Maas. The northern flow keeps the name [dblookup('Northern Flow', 'Name') -> IJssel] IJssel until it flows into [dblookup('IJssel', 'Terminates At') -> Lake IJsselmeer] Lake IJsselmeer. Three more flows carry significant amounts of water: the Nieuwe Merwede ("New Merwede"), which branches off from the southern branch where it changes from [dblookup('Boven Merwede', 'Renamed To') -> Beneden Merwede] Boven to Beneden Merwede; the [dblookup('Oude Maas', 'Source Branch') -> Southern Branch] Oude Maas ("Old Meuse"), which branches off from the southern branch where it changes from [dblookup('Beneden Merwede', 'Renamed To') -> Noord] Beneden Merwede into Noord, and [dblookup('Dordtse Kil', 'Source Branch') -> Oude Maas] Dordtse Kil, which branches off from Oude Maas.
examples.text: Rhine: The shape of the Rhine delta is determined by two bifurcations: first, at Millingen aan de Rijn, the Rhine splits into Waal and Pannerdens Kanaal, which changes its name to Nederrijn at Angeren, and second near Arnhem, the IJssel branches off from the Nederrijn. This creates three main flows, two of which change names rather often. The largest and southern main branch begins as Waal and continues as Boven Merwede ("Upper Merwede"), Beneden Merwede ("Lower Merwede"), Noord River ("North River"), Nieuwe Maas ("New Meuse"), Het Scheur ("the Rip") and Nieuwe Waterweg ("New Waterway"). The middle flow begins as Nederrijn, then changes into Lek, then joins the Noord, thereby forming Nieuwe Maas. The northern flow keeps the name IJssel until it flows into Lake IJsselmeer. Three more flows carry significant amounts of water: the Nieuwe Merwede ("New Merwede"), which branches off from the southern branch where it changes from Boven to Beneden Merwede; the Oude Maas ("Old Meuse"), which branches off from the southern branch where it changes from Beneden Merwede into Noord, and Dordtse Kil, which branches off from Oude Maas.

examples.annotated_text: Imperialism: Some have described the internal strife between various people groups as a form of [dblookup('United States', 'Internal Colonialism Concept') -> internal colonialism] imperialism or colonialism. This internal form is distinct from informal [dblookup('United States', 'Form of Informal Imperialism') -> political and financial hegemony] U.S. imperialism in the form of political and financial hegemony. This internal form of imperialism is also distinct from the United States' formation of "colonies" abroad. Through the treatment of its indigenous peoples during westward expansion, the United States took on the form of an [dblookup('United States', 'Imperialism Type') -> imperial power] imperial power prior to any attempts at external imperialism. This internal form of empire has been referred to as [dblookup('United States', 'Description of Internal Empire') -> internal colonialism] "internal colonialism". Participation in the [dblookup('United States', 'Involvement') -> African slave trade] African slave trade and the subsequent treatment of its [dblookup('African Slave Trade', 'Affected Population') -> 12 to 15 million Africans] 12 to 15 million Africans is viewed by some to be a more modern extension of America's "internal colonialism". However, this internal colonialism faced resistance, as external colonialism did, but the anti-colonial presence was far less prominent due to the nearly complete dominance that the United States was able to assert over both [dblookup('United States', 'Dominance Over') -> indigenous peoples, African-Americans] indigenous peoples and African-Americans. In his lecture on [dblookup('Edward Said', 'Lecture Date') -> April 16, 2003] April 16, 2003, Edward Said made a bold statement on modern imperialism in the United States, whom he described as using aggressive means of attack towards the [dblookup('United States', 'Aggressive Stance') -> contemporary Orient] contemporary Orient, "due to their backward living, lack of democracy and the violation of women’s rights. The western world forgets during this process of converting the other that enlightenment and democracy are concepts that not all will agree upon".
examples.text: Imperialism: Some have described the internal strife between various people groups as a form of imperialism or colonialism. However, this internal colonialism faced resistance, as external colonialism did, but the anti-colonial presence was far less prominent due to the nearly complete dominance that the United States was able to assert over both indigenous peoples and African-Americans. In his lecture on April 16, 2003, Edward Said made a bold statement on modern imperialism in the United States, whom he described as using aggressive means of attack towards the contemporary Orient, "due to their backward living, lack of democracy and the violation of women’s rights. The western world forgets during this process of converting the other that enlightenment and democracy are concepts that not all will agree upon".

examples.annotated_text: Yuan_dynasty: The final years of the Yuan dynasty were marked by struggle, famine, and bitterness among the populace. In time, [dblookup('Yuan dynasty', 'Loss of Influence Under') -> Kublai Khan's successors] Kublai Khan's successors lost all influence on other Mongol lands across Asia, while the Mongols beyond the Middle Kingdom saw them as [dblookup('Kublai Khan's Successors', 'Perception By Mongols') -> too Chinese] too Chinese. Gradually, they lost influence in China as well. The [dblookup('Yuan dynasty', 'Later Emperors' Reign Characteristics') -> short, marked by intrigues and rivalries] reigns of the later Yuan emperors were short and marked by intrigues and rivalries. Uninterested in administration, they were separated from both the army and the populace, and China was torn by dissension and unrest. Outlaws ravaged the country without interference from the weakening Yuan armies.

examples.annotated_text: Economic_inequality: For most of human history, higher material living standards led to better health and longer lives. This pattern of [dblookup('Life Expectancy', 'Correlation With') -> Higher Incomes] higher incomes-longer lives still holds among poorer countries, where life expectancy increases rapidly as per capita income increases. However, in recent decades, it has slowed down among [dblookup('Life Expectancy', 'Slowed Among') -> Middle Income Countries] middle income countries and plateaued among [dblookup('Life Expectancy', 'Stable Among') -> Richest Countries] the richest thirty or so countries in the world. Americans live no longer on average (about [dblookup('Life Expectancy in USA', 'Years in 2004') -> 77] 77 years in 2004) than Greeks ([dblookup('Life Expectancy in Greece', 'Years') -> 78] 78 years) or New Zealanders ([dblookup('Life Expectancy in New Zealand', 'Years') -> 78] 78), though the USA has a higher GDP per capita. Life expectancy in Sweden ([dblookup('Life Expectancy in Sweden', 'Years') -> 80] 80 years) and Japan ([dblookup('Life Expectancy in Japan', 'Years') -> 82] 82) – where income was more equally distributed – was longer.
examples.text: Economic_inequality: For most of human history higher material living standards – full stomachs, access to clean water and warmth from fuel – led to better health and longer lives. This pattern of higher incomes-longer lives still holds among poorer countries, where life expectancy increases rapidly as per capita income increases, but in recent decades it has slowed down among middle income countries and plateaued among the richest thirty or so countries in the world. Americans live no longer on average (about 77 years in 2004) than Greeks (78 years) or New Zealanders (78), though the USA has a higher GDP per capita. Life expectancy in Sweden (80 years) and Japan (82) – where income was more equally distributed – was longer.

examples.annotated_text: Warsaw: Gothic architecture is represented in the majestic churches but also at the burgher houses and fortifications. The most significant buildings are [dblookup('St. John\'s Cathedral, Warsaw', 'Construction Date') -> 14th century] St. John's Cathedral (14th century), the temple is a typical example of the so-called Masovian gothic style, [dblookup('St. Mary\'s Church, Warsaw', 'Construction Date') -> 1411] St. Mary's Church (1411), a town house of [dblookup('Burbach Family Town House, Warsaw', 'Construction Date') -> 14th century] Burbach family (14th century), [dblookup('Gunpowder Tower, Warsaw', 'Construction Date') -> after 1379] Gunpowder Tower (after 1379) and the [dblookup('Royal Castle Curia Maior, Warsaw', 'Construction Date') -> 1407–1410] Royal Castle Curia Maior (1407–1410). The most notable examples of Renaissance architecture in the city are the [dblookup('Baryczko House, Warsaw', 'Construction Date') -> 1562] house of Baryczko merchant family (1562), building called "The Negro" [dblookup('Building "The Negro", Warsaw', 'Construction Date') -> early 17th century] (early 17th century) and [dblookup('Salwator Tenement, Warsaw', 'Construction Date') -> 1632] Salwator tenement (1632). The most interesting examples of mannerist architecture are the [dblookup('Royal Castle, Warsaw', 'Mannerist Construction Date') -> 1596–1619] Royal Castle (1596–1619) and the [dblookup('Jesuit Church, Warsaw', 'Construction Date') -> 1609–1626] Jesuit Church (1609–1626) at Old Town. Among the first structures of the early baroque the most important are [dblookup('St. Hyacinth\'s Church, Warsaw', 'Construction Date') -> 1603–1639] St. Hyacinth's Church (1603–1639) and [dblookup('Sigismund\'s Column, Warsaw', 'Construction Date') -> 1644] Sigismund's Column (1644).
examples.text: Warsaw: Gothic architecture is represented in the majestic churches but also at the burgher houses and fortifications. The most significant buildings are St. John's Cathedral (14th century), the temple is a typical example of the so-called Masovian gothic style, St. Mary's Church (1411), a town house of Burbach family (14th century), Gunpowder Tower (after 1379) and the Royal Castle Curia Maior (1407–1410). The most notable examples of Renaissance architecture in the city are the house of Baryczko merchant family (1562), building called "The Negro" (early 17th century) and Salwator tenement (1632). The most interesting examples of mannerist architecture are the Royal Castle (1596–1619) and the Jesuit Church (1609–1626) at Old Town. Among the first structures of the early baroque the most important are St. Hyacinth's Church (1603–1639) and Sigismund's Column (1644).

examples.annotated_text: Huguenot: Around [dblookup('Huguenot Refugees', 'Migration Period') -> 1685] 1685, Huguenot refugees found a safe haven in the [dblookup('Huguenot Refugees', 'Safe Haven Locations') -> Lutheran and Reformed states in Germany and Scandinavia] Lutheran and Reformed states in Germany and Scandinavia. Nearly [dblookup('Huguenot Refugees', 'Number Settled in Germany') -> 50,000] 50,000 Huguenots established themselves in Germany, [dblookup('Huguenot Refugees', 'Number Settled in Brandenburg-Prussia') -> 20,000] 20,000 of whom were welcomed in Brandenburg-Prussia, where they were granted special privileges ( Edict of Potsdam) and churches in which to worship (such as the [dblookup('Brandenburg-Prussia', 'Churches Granted to Huguenots') -> Church of St. Peter and St. Paul, Angermünde] Church of St. Peter and St. Paul, Angermünde) by [dblookup('Huguenot Refugees', 'Privileges Granted By') -> Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg and Duke of Prussia] Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg and Duke of Prussia. The Huguenots furnished [dblookup('Huguenot Refugees', 'Military Contribution in Brandenburg-Prussia') -> two new regiments] two new regiments of his army: the [dblookup('Altpreußische Infantry Regiment No. 13', 'Huguenot Regiment Name') -> Regiment on foot Varenne] Altpreußische Infantry Regiments No. 13 (Regiment on foot Varenne) and [dblookup('Altpreußische Infantry Regiment No. 15', 'Huguenot Regiment Name') -> Regiment on foot Wylich] 15 (Regiment on foot Wylich). Another [dblookup('Huguenot Refugees', 'Number Settled in Other German Territories') -> 4,000] 4,000 Huguenots settled in the German territories of [dblookup('Huguenot Refugees', 'Other German Territories Settled In') -> Baden, Franconia, Landgraviate of Hesse-Kassel, Duchy of Württemberg, Wetterau Association of Imperial Counts, Palatinate, Palatinate-Zweibrücken, Rhine-Main-Area, Saarland] Baden, Franconia (Principality of Bayreuth, Principality of Ansbach), Landgraviate of Hesse-Kassel, Duchy of Württemberg, in the Wetterau Association of Imperial Counts, in the Palatinate and Palatinate-Zweibrücken, in the Rhine-Main-Area (Frankfurt), in modern-day Saarland; and [dblookup('Huguenot Refugees', 'Number Settled in Hamburg, Bremen, Lower Saxony') -> 1,500] 1,500 found refuge in Hamburg, Bremen and Lower Saxony. [dblookup('Huguenot Refugees', 'Number Granted Asylum by George William') -> Three hundred] Three hundred refugees were granted asylum at the court of [dblookup('George William', 'Refugees Granted Asylum') -> Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg in Celle] George William, Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg in Celle.
examples.text: Huguenot: Around 1685, Huguenot refugees found a safe haven in the Lutheran and Reformed states in Germany and Scandinavia. Nearly 50,000 Huguenots established themselves in Germany, 20,000 of whom were welcomed in Brandenburg-Prussia, where they were granted special privileges (Edict of Potsdam) and churches in which to worship (such as the Church of St. Peter and St. Paul, Angermünde) by Frederick William, Elector of Brandenburg and Duke of Prussia. The Huguenots furnished two new regiments of his army: the Altpreußische Infantry Regiments No. 13 (Regiment on foot Varenne) and 15 (Regiment on foot Wylich). Another 4,000 Huguenots settled in the German territories of Baden, Franconia (Principality of Bayreuth, Principality of Ansbach), Landgraviate of Hesse-Kassel, Duchy of Württemberg, in the Wetterau Association of Imperial Counts, in the Palatinate and Palatinate-Zweibrücken, in the Rhine-Main-Area (Frankfurt), in modern-day Saarland; and 1,500 found refuge in Hamburg, Bremen and Lower Saxony. Three hundred refugees were granted asylum at the court of George William, Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg in Celle.

examples.annotated_text: Islamism: After [dblookup('Gaafar al-Nimeiry', 'Overthrow Year') -> 1985] al-Nimeiry was overthrown in 1985 the party did poorly in national elections, but in [dblookup('Sudan Coup', 'Year Occurred') -> 1989] 1989 it was able to overthrow the elected post-al-Nimeiry government with the help of the military. [dblookup('Hassan al-Turabi', 'Political Stance Before Power') -> Support for democratic process and liberal government] Turabi was noted for proclaiming his support for the democratic process and a liberal government before coming to power, but strict application of sharia law, torture and mass imprisonment of the opposition, and an intensification of the long-running war in southern Sudan, once in power. The [dblookup('National Islamic Front', 'Leader') -> Hassan al-Turabi] NIF regime also harbored Osama bin Laden for a time (before 9/11), and worked to [dblookup('National Islamic Front', 'Policy During 1991 Gulf War') -> Unify Islamist opposition to American attack on Iraq] unify Islamist opposition to the American attack on Iraq in the 1991 Gulf War.
examples.text: Islamism: After al-Nimeiry was overthrown in 1985 the party did poorly in national elections, but in 1989 it was able to overthrow the elected post-al-Nimeiry government with the help of the military. Turabi was noted for proclaiming his support for the democratic process and a liberal government before coming to power, but strict application of sharia law, torture and mass imprisonment of the opposition, and an intensification of the long-running war in southern Sudan, once in power. The NIF regime also harbored Osama bin Laden for a time (before 9/11), and worked to unify Islamist opposition to the American attack on Iraq in the 1991 Gulf War.

examples.annotated_text: Pharmacy: In most jurisdictions (such as [dblookup('United States', 'Pharmacists Regulation') -> separately from physicians] the United States), pharmacists are regulated separately from physicians. These jurisdictions also usually specify that only pharmacists may supply scheduled pharmaceuticals to the public, and that [dblookup('Jurisdictions', 'Pharmacists Business Restrictions') -> cannot form business partnerships with physicians or give kickback payments] pharmacists cannot form business partnerships with physicians or give them "kickback" payments. However, the [dblookup('American Medical Association', 'Code of Ethics Provision on Dispensing') -> allows physicians to dispense drugs within office practices] American Medical Association (AMA) Code of Ethics provides that physicians may dispense drugs within their office practices as long as there is no patient exploitation and patients have the right to a written prescription that can be filled elsewhere. 7 to 10 percent of American physicians practices reportedly dispense drugs on their own.
examples.text: Pharmacy: In most jurisdictions (such as the United States), pharmacists are regulated separately from physicians. These jurisdictions also usually specify that only pharmacists may supply scheduled pharmaceuticals to the public, and that pharmacists cannot form business partnerships with physicians or give them "kickback" payments. However, the American Medical Association (AMA) Code of Ethics provides that physicians may dispense drugs within their office practices as long as there is no patient exploitation and patients have the right to a written prescription that can be filled elsewhere. 7 to 10 percent of American physicians practices reportedly dispense drugs on their own.

examples.annotated_text: European_Union_law: The primary law of the EU consists mainly of the founding treaties, the "core" treaties being the [dblookup('European Union Law', 'Core Treaties') -> Treaty on European Union, Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union] Treaty on European Union (TEU) and the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU). The Treaties contain formal and substantive provisions, which frame policies of the European Union institutions and determine the [dblookup('European Union Law', 'Division of Competences') -> European Union, Member States] division of competences between the European Union and its member states. The TEU establishes that [dblookup('TEU', 'Territorial Application') -> metropolitan territories of Member States; certain islands and overseas territories like Madeira, Canary Islands, French overseas departments] European Union law applies to the metropolitan territories of the member states, as well as certain islands and overseas territories, including Madeira, the Canary Islands and the French overseas departments. European Union law also applies in [dblookup('EU Member States', 'External Relations Territory Application') -> Gibraltar, Åland islands] territories where a member state is responsible for external relations, for example Gibraltar and the Åland islands. The TEU allows the European Council to make specific provisions for regions, as for example done for [dblookup('TEU', 'Customs Matters Provisions') -> Gibraltar, Saint-Pierre-et-Miquelon] customs matters in Gibraltar and Saint-Pierre-et-Miquelon. The TEU specifically [dblookup('TEU', 'Excluded Regions') -> Faroe Islands] excludes certain regions, for example the Faroe Islands, from the jurisdiction of European Union law. Treaties apply as soon as they enter into force, unless stated otherwise, and are generally concluded for [dblookup('EU Treaties', 'Duration') -> unlimited period] an unlimited period. The TEU provides that commitments entered into by the member states between themselves before the treaty was signed no longer apply. All EU member states are regarded as subject to the [dblookup('TEU', 'Principle of Cooperation') -> general obligation] general obligation of the principle of cooperation, as stated in the TEU, whereby member states are obliged not to take measures which could jeopardise the attainment of the TEU objectives. The Court of Justice of the European Union can interpret the Treaties, but it cannot rule on their validity, which is subject to international law. Individuals may rely on primary law in the Court of Justice of the European Union if the Treaty provisions have a [dblookup('TEU Provisions', 'Direct Effect Criteria') -> direct effect; clear, precise, unconditional] direct effect and they are sufficiently clear, precise and unconditional.
examples.text: European_Union_law: The primary law of the EU consists mainly of the founding treaties, the "core" treaties being the Treaty on European Union (TEU) and the Treaty on the Functioning of the European Union (TFEU). The Treaties contain formal and substantive provisions, which frame policies of the European Union institutions and determine the division of competences between the European Union and its member states. The TEU establishes that European Union law applies to the metropolitan territories of the member states, as well as certain islands and overseas territories, including Madeira, the Canary Islands and the French overseas departments. European Union law also applies in territories where a member state is responsible for external relations, for example Gibraltar and the Åland islands. The TEU allows the European Council to make specific provisions for regions, as for example done for customs matters in Gibraltar and Saint-Pierre-et-Miquelon. The TEU specifically excludes certain regions, for example the Faroe Islands, from the jurisdiction of European Union law. Treaties apply as soon as they enter into force, unless stated otherwise, and are generally concluded for an unlimited period. The TEU provides that commitments entered into by the member states between themselves before the treaty was signed no longer apply.[vague] All EU member states are regarded as subject to the general obligation of the principle of cooperation, as stated in the TEU, whereby member states are obliged not to take measure which could jeopardise the attainment of the TEU objectives. The Court of Justice of the European Union can interpret the Treaties, but it cannot rule on their validity, which is subject to international law. Individuals may rely on primary law in the Court of Justice of the European Union if the Treaty provisions have a direct effect and they are sufficiently clear, precise and unconditional.

examples.annotated_text: 1973_oil_crisis: [dblookup('1973 oil crisis', 'Exacerbated By') -> Price controls] Price controls exacerbated the crisis in the US. The system limited the price of "old oil" (that which had already been discovered) while allowing [dblookup('1973 oil crisis', 'Higher Price Allowance') -> newly discovered oil] newly discovered oil to be sold at a higher price to encourage investment. Predictably, old oil was [dblookup('1973 oil crisis', 'Effect on Old Oil') -> withdrawn from the market] withdrawn from the market, creating greater scarcity. The rule also discouraged [dblookup('1973 oil crisis', 'Discouraged Development') -> alternative energies] development of alternative energies. The rule had been intended to [dblookup('1973 oil crisis', 'Intended Purpose') -> promote oil exploration] promote oil exploration. Scarcity was addressed by [dblookup('1973 oil crisis', 'Scarcity Addressed By') -> rationing] rationing (as in many countries). Motorists faced [dblookup('1973 oil crisis', 'Effect on Motorists') -> long lines at gas stations] long lines at gas stations beginning in summer 1972 and increasing by summer 1973.
examples.text: 1973_oil_crisis: Price controls exacerbated the crisis in the US. The system limited the price of "old oil" (that which had already been discovered) while allowing newly discovered oil to be sold at a higher price to encourage investment. Predictably, old oil was withdrawn from the market, creating greater scarcity. The rule also discouraged development of alternative energies. The rule had been intended to promote oil exploration. Scarcity was addressed by rationing (as in many countries). Motorists faced long lines at gas stations beginning in summer 1972 and increasing by summer 1973.

examples.annotated_text: Packet_switching: AUSTPAC was an Australian public [dblookup('AUSTPAC', 'Technology') -> X.25 network] X.25 network operated by [dblookup('AUSTPAC', 'Operator') -> Telstra] Telstra. Started by [dblookup('AUSTPAC', 'Initiated By') -> Telecom Australia] Telecom Australia in the early [dblookup('AUSTPAC', 'Decade Started') -> 1980s] 1980s, AUSTPAC was [dblookup('AUSTPAC', 'Significance') -> Australia's first public packet-switched data network] Australia's first public packet-switched data network, supporting applications such as on-line betting, financial applications — the Australian Tax Office made use of AUSTPAC — and remote terminal access to academic institutions, who maintained their connections to AUSTPAC up until the mid-late 1990s in some cases. Access can be via a dial-up terminal to a PAD, or, by linking a permanent X.25 node to the network.
examples.text: Packet_switching: AUSTPAC was an Australian public X.25 network operated by Telstra. Started by Telecom Australia in the early 1980s, AUSTPAC was Australia's first public packet-switched data network, supporting applications such as on-line betting, financial applications — the Australian Tax Office made use of AUSTPAC — and remote terminal access to academic institutions, who maintained their connections to AUSTPAC up until the mid-late 1990s in some cases. Access can be via a dial-up terminal to a PAD, or, by linking a permanent X.25 node to the network.[citation needed]

examples.annotated_text: Immune_system: Immunology is strongly experimental in everyday practice but is also characterized by an ongoing theoretical attitude. Many theories have been suggested in immunology from the end of the nineteenth century up to the present time. The end of the 19th century and the beginning of the 20th century saw a battle between [dblookup('Theories of Immunity', 'Competing Theories') -> cellular and humoral] "cellular" and "humoral" theories of immunity. According to the [dblookup('Cellular Theory of Immunity', 'Proponent') -> Elie Metchnikoff] cellular theory of immunity, represented in particular by Elie Metchnikoff, it was cells – more precisely, [dblookup('Cellular Theory of Immunity', 'Mechanism') -> phagocytes] phagocytes – that were responsible for immune responses. In contrast, the [dblookup('Humoral Theory of Immunity', 'Proponents') -> Robert Koch, Emil von Behring] humoral theory of immunity, held, among others, by Robert Koch and Emil von Behring, stated that the active immune agents were [dblookup('Humoral Theory of Immunity', 'Mechanism') -> soluble components in humors] soluble components (molecules) found in the organism’s “humors” rather than its cells.
examples.text: Immune_system: Immunology is strongly experimental in everyday practice but is also characterized by an ongoing theoretical attitude. Many theories have been suggested in immunology from the end of the nineteenth century up to the present time. The end of the 19th century and the beginning of the 20th century saw a battle between "cellular" and "humoral" theories of immunity. According to the cellular theory of immunity, represented in particular by Elie Metchnikoff, it was cells – more precisely, phagocytes – that were responsible for immune responses. In contrast, the humoral theory of immunity, held, among others, by Robert Koch and Emil von Behring, stated that the active immune agents were soluble components (molecules) found in the organism’s “humors” rather than its cells.

examples.annotated_text: Economic_inequality: In Marxian analysis, capitalist firms increasingly substitute [dblookup('Capitalist Firms', 'Substitute') -> capital equipment for labor inputs] capital equipment for labor inputs (workers) under competitive pressure to reduce costs and maximize profits. Over the long-term, this trend [dblookup('Capitalist Firms', 'Effect Of Substituting Capital') -> increases organic composition of capital] increases the organic composition of capital, meaning that [dblookup('Organic Composition Of Capital', 'Effect') -> less workers required] less workers are required in proportion to capital inputs, increasing unemployment (the "reserve army of labour"). This process [dblookup('Reserve Army of Labour', 'Effect On Wages') -> downward pressure] exerts a downward pressure on wages. The substitution of capital equipment for labor (mechanization and automation) [dblookup('Mechanization', 'Effect On Productivity') -> raises worker productivity] raises the productivity of each worker, resulting in [dblookup('Mechanization', 'Effect On Wages') -> stagnant wages] a situation of relatively stagnant wages for the working class amidst [dblookup('Capitalist Class', 'Income Trend') -> rising property income] rising levels of property income for the capitalist class.
examples.text: Economic_inequality: In Marxian analysis, capitalist firms increasingly substitute capital equipment for labor inputs (workers) under competitive pressure to reduce costs and maximize profits. Over the long-term, this trend increases the organic composition of capital, meaning that less workers are required in proportion to capital inputs, increasing unemployment (the "reserve army of labour"). This process exerts a downward pressure on wages. The substitution of capital equipment for labor (mechanization and automation) raises the productivity of each worker, resulting in a situation of relatively stagnant wages for the working class amidst rising levels of property income for the capitalist class.

examples.annotated_text: Steam_engine: Although the reciprocating steam engine is no longer in widespread commercial use, various companies are exploring or exploiting the potential of the engine as an alternative to internal combustion engines. The company Energiprojekt AB in Sweden has made progress in using modern materials for harnessing the power of steam. The [dblookup('Energiprojekt AB', 'Steam Engine Efficiency') -> 27-30%] efficiency of Energiprojekt's steam engine reaches some 27-30% on high-pressure engines. It is a [dblookup('Energiprojekt AB Steam Engine', 'Design') -> single-step, 5-cylinder engine] single-step, 5-cylinder engine (no compound) with [dblookup('Energiprojekt AB Steam Engine', 'Type of Steam') -> superheated] superheated steam and consumes approx. [dblookup('Energiprojekt AB Steam Engine', 'Steam Consumption Per kWh') -> 4 kg] 4 kg (8.8 lb) of steam per kWh.
examples.text: Steam_engine: Although the reciprocating steam engine is no longer in widespread commercial use, various companies are exploring or exploiting the potential of the engine as an alternative to internal combustion engines. The company Energiprojekt AB in Sweden has made progress in using modern materials for harnessing the power of steam. The efficiency of Energiprojekt's steam engine reaches some 27-30% on high-pressure engines. It is a single-step, 5-cylinder engine (no compound) with superheated steam and consumes approx. 4 kg (8.8 lb) of steam per kWh.[not in citation given]

examples.annotated_text: Yuan_dynasty: Kublai Khan promoted [dblookup('Kublai Khan', 'Promoted Areas') -> commercial, scientific, cultural growth] commercial, scientific, and cultural growth. He supported the [dblookup('Kublai Khan', 'Supported Group') -> Silk Road merchants] merchants of the Silk Road trade network by [dblookup('Kublai Khan', 'Supported With') -> protecting Mongol postal system, constructing infrastructure, providing loans, encouraging paper banknotes circulation] protecting the Mongol postal system, constructing infrastructure, providing loans that financed trade caravans, and encouraging the circulation of paper banknotes (鈔, Chao). [dblookup('Pax Mongolica', 'Effect') -> Spread of technologies, commodities, culture between China and West] Pax Mongolica, Mongol peace, enabled the spread of technologies, commodities, and culture between China and the West. Kublai expanded the Grand Canal from southern China to Daidu in the north. Mongol rule was [dblookup('Mongol Rule Under Kublai Khan', 'Character') -> cosmopolitan] cosmopolitan under Kublai Khan. He welcomed [dblookup('Kublai Khan', 'Welcomed Visitors') -> Marco Polo] foreign visitors to his court, such as the Venetian merchant Marco Polo, who [dblookup('Marco Polo', 'Writings Influence On') -> European account of Yuan China] wrote the most influential European account of Yuan China. Marco Polo's travels would later [dblookup('Marco Polo', 'Inspired') -> Christopher Columbus] inspire many others like Christopher Columbus to chart a passage to the Far East in search of its legendary wealth.
examples.text: Yuan_dynasty: Kublai Khan promoted commercial, scientific, and cultural growth. He supported the merchants of the Silk Road trade network by protecting the Mongol postal system, constructing infrastructure, providing loans that financed trade caravans, and encouraging the circulation of paper banknotes (鈔, Chao). Pax Mongolica, Mongol peace, enabled the spread of technologies, commodities, and culture between China and the West. Kublai expanded the Grand Canal from southern China to Daidu in the north. Mongol rule was cosmopolitan under Kublai Khan. He welcomed foreign visitors to his court, such as the Venetian merchant Marco Polo, who wrote the most influential European account of Yuan China. Marco Polo's travels would later inspire many others like Christopher Columbus to chart a passage to the Far East in search of its legendary wealth.

examples.annotated_text: Oxygen: Planetary geologists have measured different abundances of oxygen isotopes in samples from the Earth, the Moon, Mars, and meteorites, but were long unable to obtain reference values for the isotope ratios in the [dblookup('Sun', 'Reference Values Believed Same As') -> primordial solar nebula] Sun, believed to be the same as those of the primordial solar nebula. Analysis of a silicon wafer exposed to the solar wind in space and returned by the crashed [dblookup('Genesis Spacecraft', 'Mission Outcome') -> crashed] Genesis spacecraft has shown that the Sun has a higher proportion of oxygen-16 than does the Earth. The measurement implies that an unknown process depleted [dblookup('Oxygen-16', 'Depleted From') -> Sun's disk of protoplanetary material] oxygen-16 from the Sun's disk of protoplanetary material prior to the coalescence of dust grains that formed the Earth.
examples.text: Oxygen: Planetary geologists have measured different abundances of oxygen isotopes in samples from the Earth, the Moon, Mars, and meteorites, but were long unable to obtain reference values for the isotope ratios in the Sun, believed to be the same as those of the primordial solar nebula. Analysis of a silicon wafer exposed to the solar wind in space and returned by the crashed Genesis spacecraft has shown that the Sun has a higher proportion of oxygen-16 than does the Earth. The measurement implies that an unknown process depleted oxygen-16 from the Sun's disk of protoplanetary material prior to the coalescence of dust grains that formed the Earth.

examples.annotated_text: Oxygen: In 1891 Scottish chemist [dblookup('James Dewar', 'Nationality') -> Scottish] James Dewar was able to produce enough [dblookup('James Dewar', 'Scientific Achievement') -> liquid oxygen production] liquid oxygen to study. The first commercially viable process for producing liquid oxygen was independently developed in [dblookup('Carl von Linde', 'Liquid Oxygen Process Year') -> 1895] 1895 by [dblookup('Carl von Linde', 'Nationality') -> German] German engineer [dblookup('Carl von Linde', 'Achievement') -> liquid oxygen production process] Carl von Linde and [dblookup('William Hampson', 'Nationality') -> British] British engineer [dblookup('William Hampson', 'Achievement') -> liquid oxygen production process] William Hampson. Both men lowered the temperature of air until it liquefied and then distilled the component gases by boiling them off one at a time and capturing them. Later, in [dblookup('Oxyacetylene Welding', 'First Demonstrated') -> 1901] 1901, oxyacetylene welding was demonstrated for the first time by burning a mixture of acetylene and compressed O2. This method of welding and cutting metal later became [dblookup('Oxyacetylene Welding', 'Common Usage') -> welding and cutting metal] common.
examples.text:
Oxygen: In 1891 Scottish chemist James Dewar was able to produce enough liquid oxygen to study. The first commercially viable process for producing liquid oxygen was independently developed in 1895 by German engineer Carl von Linde and British engineer William Hampson. Both men lowered the temperature of air until it liquefied and then distilled the component gases by boiling them off one at a time and capturing them. Later, in 1901, oxyacetylene welding was demonstrated for the first time by burning a mixture of acetylene and compressed O
2. This method of welding and cutting metal later became common.

examples.annotated_text: Intergovernmental_Panel_on_Climate_Change: The executive summary of the WG I Summary for Policymakers report says they are [dblookup('Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change', 'Certainty About Human Activity Impact') -> certain that emissions resulting from human activities are substantially increasing the atmospheric concentrations of greenhouse gases] certain that emissions resulting from human activities are substantially increasing the atmospheric concentrations of the greenhouse gases, resulting on average in an additional warming of the Earth's surface. They [dblookup('Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change', 'Major Greenhouse Gas Responsible') -> CO2] calculate with confidence that CO2 has been responsible for over half the enhanced greenhouse effect. They predict that under a [dblookup('Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change', 'Scenario Name') -> business as usual (BAU)] "business as usual" (BAU) scenario, [dblookup('Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change', 'Predicted Temperature Increase') -> 0.3 °C per decade during the 21st century] global mean temperature will increase by about 0.3 °C per decade during the 21st century. They judge that [dblookup('Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change', 'Historical Temperature Increase') -> 0.3 to 0.6 °C over the last 100 years] global mean surface air temperature has increased by 0.3 to 0.6 °C over the last 100 years, broadly consistent with prediction of climate models, but also of the same magnitude as natural climate variability. The unequivocal detection of the enhanced greenhouse effect is [dblookup('Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change', 'Detection Timeline') -> not likely for a decade or more] not likely for a decade or more.
examples.text: Intergovernmental_Panel_on_Climate_Change: The executive summary of the WG I Summary for Policymakers report says they are certain that emissions resulting from human activities are substantially increasing the atmospheric concentrations of the greenhouse gases, resulting on average in an additional warming of the Earth's surface. They calculate with confidence that CO2 has been responsible for over half the enhanced greenhouse effect. They predict that under a "business as usual" (BAU) scenario, global mean temperature will increase by about 0.3 °C per decade during the [21st] century. They judge that global mean surface air temperature has increased by 0.3 to 0.6 °C over the last 100 years, broadly consistent with prediction of climate models, but also of the same magnitude as natural climate variability. The unequivocal detection of the enhanced greenhouse effect is not likely for a decade or more.

examples.annotated_text: Black_Death: In England, in the absence of census figures, historians propose a range of [dblookup('England', 'Pre-Black Death Population Range in 1300') -> 4 million to 7 million] preincident population figures from as high as 7 million to as low as 4 million in 1300, and a [dblookup('England', 'Post-Black Death Population Figure') -> 2 million] postincident population figure as low as 2 million. By the end of [dblookup('Black Death', 'End Year in England') -> 1350] 1350, the Black Death subsided, but it never really died out in England. Over the next few hundred years, further outbreaks occurred in [dblookup('Black Death', 'Outbreak Years 14th Century in England') -> 1361–62, 1369, 1379–83, 1389–93] 1361–62, 1369, 1379–83, 1389–93, and throughout the [dblookup('Black Death', 'Outbreak Period 15th Century in England') -> first half of the 15th century] first half of the 15th century. An outbreak in [dblookup('Black Death', '1471 Outbreak Impact in England') -> 10–15% population loss] 1471 took as much as 10–15% of the population, while the death rate of the plague of [dblookup('Black Death', 'Death Rate 1479–80 Outbreak in England') -> as high as 20%] 1479–80 could have been as high as 20%. The most general outbreaks in [dblookup('Black Death', 'Outbreak Years Tudor and Stuart England') -> 1498, 1535, 1543, 1563, 1589, 1603, 1625, 1636] Tudor and Stuart England seem to have begun in 1498, 1535, 1543, 1563, 1589, 1603, 1625, and 1636, and ended with the [dblookup('Black Death', 'Final Major Outbreak in England') -> Great Plague of London in 1665] Great Plague of London in 1665.
examples.text: Black_Death: In England, in the absence of census figures, historians propose a range of preincident population figures from as high as 7 million to as low as 4 million in 1300, and a postincident population figure as low as 2 million. By the end of 1350, the Black Death subsided, but it never really died out in England. Over the next few hundred years, further outbreaks occurred in 1361–62, 1369, 1379–83, 1389–93, and throughout the first half of the 15th century. An outbreak in 1471 took as much as 10–15% of the population, while the death rate of the plague of 1479–80 could have been as high as 20%. The most general outbreaks in Tudor and Stuart England seem to have begun in 1498, 1535, 1543, 1563, 1589, 1603, 1625, and 1636, and ended with the Great Plague of London in 1665.

examples.annotated_text: Immune_system: Clearly, some tumors evade the immune system and go on to become cancers. Tumor cells often have a reduced number of MHC class I molecules on their surface, thus avoiding detection by killer T cells. Some tumor cells also release [dblookup('Tumor Cells', 'Immune Inhibition Products') -> cytokine TGF-β] products that inhibit the immune response; for example by secreting the cytokine TGF-β, which suppresses the activity of macrophages and lymphocytes. In addition, [dblookup('Immune System', 'Tolerance Development') -> tumor antigens] immunological tolerance may develop against tumor antigens, so the immune system no longer attacks the tumor cells.

examples.annotated_text: Scottish_Parliament: Throughout the 1980s and 1990s, demand for a [dblookup('Scottish Parliament', 'Demand Growth Period') -> 1980s, 1990s] Scottish Parliament grew, in part because the government of the United Kingdom was controlled by [dblookup('United Kingdom', 'Governing Party in 1980s and 1990s') -> Conservative Party] the Conservative Party, while Scotland itself elected relatively few Conservative MPs. In the aftermath of the [dblookup('1979 Referendum', 'Outcome') -> Defeat] 1979 referendum defeat, the Campaign for a Scottish Assembly was initiated as a pressure group, leading to the [dblookup('Scottish Constitutional Convention', 'Year Established') -> 1989] 1989 Scottish Constitutional Convention with various organisations such as [dblookup('Scottish Constitutional Convention', 'Participants') -> Scottish churches, political parties, industry representatives] Scottish churches, political parties and representatives of industry taking part. Publishing its blueprint for devolution in [dblookup('Scottish Constitutional Convention', 'Devolution Blueprint Publication Year') -> 1995] 1995, the Convention provided much of the basis for the structure of the Parliament.
examples.text: Scottish_Parliament: Throughout the 1980s and 1990s, demand for a Scottish Parliament grew, in part because the government of the United Kingdom was controlled by the Conservative Party, while Scotland itself elected relatively few Conservative MPs. In the aftermath of the 1979 referendum defeat, the Campaign for a Scottish Assembly was initiated as a pressure group, leading to the 1989 Scottish Constitutional Convention with various organisations such as Scottish churches, political parties and representatives of industry taking part. Publishing its blueprint for devolution in 1995, the Convention provided much of the basis for the structure of the Parliament.

examples.annotated_text: Sky_(United_Kingdom): On [dblookup('Sky', 'Announcement Date of Sky Q') -> 18 November 2015] 18 November 2015, Sky announced [dblookup('Sky Q', 'Product Launch Year') -> 2016] Sky Q, a range of products and services to be available in 2016. The Sky Q range consists of three set top boxes (Sky Q, Sky Q Silver and Sky Q Mini), a broadband router (Sky Q Hub) and mobile applications. The Sky Q set top boxes introduce [dblookup('Sky Q Set Top Boxes', 'New Features') -> new user interface, Wi-Fi hotspot functionality, Power-line and Bluetooth connectivity, touch-sensitive remote control] a new user interface, Wi-Fi hotspot functionality, Power-line and Bluetooth connectivity and a new touch-sensitive remote control. The Sky Q Mini set top boxes connect to the Sky Q Silver set top boxes with [dblookup('Sky Q Mini Set Top Boxes', 'Connection Method') -> Wi-Fi or Power-line connection] a Wi-Fi or Power-line connection rather than receive their own satellite feeds. This allows all set top boxes in a household to share recordings and other media. The Sky Q Silver set top box is capable of [dblookup('Sky Q Silver Set Top Box', 'Features') -> receiving and displaying UHD broadcasts] receiving and displaying UHD broadcasts, which Sky will introduce later in 2016.
examples.text: Sky_(United_Kingdom): On 18 November 2015, Sky announced Sky Q, a range of products and services to be available in 2016. The Sky Q range consists of three set top boxes (Sky Q, Sky Q Silver and Sky Q Mini), a broadband router (Sky Q Hub) and mobile applications. The Sky Q set top boxes introduce a new user interface, Wi-Fi hotspot functionality, Power-line and Bluetooth connectivity and a new touch-sensitive remote control. The Sky Q Mini set top boxes connect to the Sky Q Silver set top boxes with a Wi-Fi or Power-line connection rather than receive their own satellite feeds. This allows all set top boxes in a household to share recordings and other media. The Sky Q Silver set top box is capable of receiving and displaying UHD broadcasts, which Sky will introduce later in 2016.
